irus in Palestine: Suspected cases near Bethlehem|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-palestine-bethlehem-nativity-church-mosques-middle-east|website=Middle East Eye}}</ref> The [[Health Minister of the State of Palestine|Palestinian health ministry]] said the cases had first been detected at a hotel in the Bethlehem area, where a group of Greek tourists had visited the hotel in late February, with two later diagnosed with the virus.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The [[Church of the Nativity]] is expected to close after 2 Greek visitors that later tested positive were visiting hotels in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/church-nativity-bethlehem-close-coronavirus-fears-200305111108893.html|title=Church of Nativity in Bethlehem to close over coronavirus fears|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n*As a result, the Palestinian government announced a complete ban on entry of foreign tourists.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestinians announce West Bank tourism ban over coronavirus|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200305-palestinians-announce-west-bank-tourism-ban-over-coronavirus|publisher=France24|date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> The [[Palestinian government]] declared a [[state of emergency]] in the [[West Bank]] on 5 March.<ref>{{cite web|first1=T. O. I.|last1=staff|last2=Agencies|accessdate=2020-03-06|title=PA shutters West Bank, Israel quarantines Bethlehem after coronavirus found|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/pa-shutters-west-bank-israel-quarantines-bethlehem-after-coronavirus-found/|website=www.timesofisrael.com}}</ref> Schools, universities, mosques and churches were closed for one month.\n \n'''7 March:'''\n* On 7 March, there were 22 cases of infections.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by Johns Hopkins CSSE |url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 |website=gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com |accessdate=3 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307233133/https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 |archivedate=7 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The City of Bethlehem is locked down as 16 cases of infection are found in the West Bank, including nine cases in Bethlehem.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/bethlehem-lockdown-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-200307054939115.html|title=Bethlehem under lockdown after coronavirus cases confirmed|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> The lockdown is imposed by Israeli military as [[Israel]] controlled all entrances to the West Bank. According to the Israeli defense ministry, the lockdown of Bethlehem is imposed in coordination with [[Palestinian government|Palestinian authorities]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bethlehem Becomes a Ghost Town After Coronavirus Closure|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/palestinians/.premium-bethlehem-becomes-a-ghost-town-after-coronavirus-closure-1.8635434|publisher=Haaretz|date=March 8, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''9 March:'''\n* Palestinian authorities announce that there are 5 more cases on the West Bank. Four cases were recorded in Bethlehem, and one in [[Tulkarm]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/health/palestine-confirms-5-more-coronavirus-cases/1759584|title=Palestine confirms 5 more coronavirus cases|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n'''13 March''' \n* The [[Palestinian Ministry of Health]] (MOH) confirmed 35 coronavirus cases on March 13, mostly concentrated in the [[Bethlehem Governorate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.pnn.ps/2020/03/13/the-risk-remains-very-high-35-cases-of-corona-virus-disease-palestine/|title=The risk remains very high: 35 cases of Corona virus disease Palestine|website=PNN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n'''14 March'''\n* 3 new cases has been announced, bringing the total to 38 cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/latest-on-coronavirus-outbreak/palestine-reports-3-new-coronavirus-cases-in-bethlehem/1766049|title=Palestine reports 3 new coronavirus cases in Bethlehem|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n'''16 March'''\n\n*A second case was confirmed in [[Tulkarm]] raising the number in Palestine to 39. [[Prime Minister of the State of Palestine|Prime Minister]] [[Mohammad Shtayyeh]] said that [[Kuwait]] has contributed $5.5 million to help the Palestinians overcome coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=New coronavirus case confirmed in Palestine|url=https://en.royanews.tv/news/20257/New-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-Palestine|publisher=Roya News|date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) Update 9 |url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=D3691469D7D454792540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0 |publisher=WHO |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''18 March'''\n\n*The number of cases has risen to 44.<ref>{{cite news |title=Live Updates Israeli Coronavirus Diagnoses Spike by 27 Percent, Top Brass to Prepare for Full Lockdown |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/israeli-coronavirus-diagnoses-spike-by-27-percent-new-west-bank-cases-emerge-1.8686074|publisher=Haaretz|date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> 40 cases are from Bethlehem, two from [[Tulkarm]], one from [[Ramallah]] and another from [[Nablus]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms three new coronavirus cases |url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=QxwF1Ta115429555593aQxwF1T|publisher=Wafa|date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) Update 10 |url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=36FB93A72013F4462540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0 |publisher=WHO |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Ministry of Defense (Israel)|Israeli Minister of Defense]], Naftali Bennett said \"Starting Wednesday, those West Bank-based Palestinians, who happen to work or trade in vital sectors, such as health, agriculture and building, can reside in Israel\u201d. More than 100,000 Palestinian workers from the West Bank who work in Israel, usually return home on a daily basis.<ref>{{cite news |title=Due to Corona, Israel to Let Palestinian Workers Stay in Workplaces|url=https://imemc.org/article/due-to-corona-israel-to-let-palestinian-workers-stay-in-workplaces/|publisher=IMEMC|date=March 17, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n*Yotam Shefer of [[Coordinator of Government Activities in the Territories|COGAT]] announced the closing of Palestinian-administered areas of the West Bank on Wednesday to limit the spread of coronavirus, telling journalists the decision had been made in conjunction with the [[Palestinian Authority]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coordinating with Abbas, Israel puts virus closure on PA-ruled West Bank areas|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-imposes-virus-closure-on-palestinian-ruled-areas-of-west-bank/|publisher=Timews of Israel|date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n*Israel and the Palestinian Authority have set up a joint operations room to combat the pandemic, PA government spokesman Ibrahim Milhem revealed. An Israeli Defense Ministry official confirmed that a joint operations room has been set up with the Palestinians, but declined to provide further details.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israel, Palestinians set up joint operations room to combat coronavirus|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Israel-Palestinians-set-up-joint-operations-room-to-combat-coronavirus-621431|publisher=Jerusalem Post|date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n*The United Nations Humanitarian Coordinator for the occupied Palestinian Territories Jamie McGoldrick announced during a video conference with Mohammed Shtayyeh one million dollars of urgent joint financial support from multiple United Nations organizations to provide health aid and technical support to Palestine to help it confront the outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |title=UN official applauds Palestinians' efforts to cope with Coronavirus|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=KOgfMha115437169617aKOgfMh|publisher=WAFA|date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''19 March'''\n\n*Ibrahim Milhem confirmed three new cases bringing the total to 47. He said in the daily briefing that two cases were students returning home from France and quarantined before being in contact with anyone. The third is for a person from Nablus previously suspected of having the disease and was kept in home quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spokesman: Three new cases of coronavirus in Palestine; total 47|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=0iwpCia115441928382a0iwpCi|publisher=WAFA|date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''20 March'''\n*The Minister of Health, Dr. Mai Al-Kaila, announced that 17 of the 19 cases who had been in quarantine in Bethlehem had recovered. The Minister said at a press conference held this Friday morning in [[Ramallah]], that 17 patients who were in health quarantine in the city of Bethlehem will be allowed, after confirming their recovery, as they will be allowed to go to the house, with an emphasis on them to adhere to the home quarantine, and taking into account the measurement of temperature from time to time. \n*The Minister also announced a new case, a [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] from [[Salfit Governorate]] coming from [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pnn.ps/news/498848 |title = \u0648\u0632\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u062d\u0629: \u0625\u0635\u0627\u0628\u0629 \u062c\u062f\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0628\u0633\u0644\u0641\u064a\u062a\u2026 \u0648\u0634\u0641\u0627\u0621 17 \u0645\u0631\u064a\u0636\u064b\u0627 \u0643\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0641\u0646\u062f\u0642 \"\u0622\u0646\u062c\u0644\" \u0628\u0628\u064a\u062a \u0644\u062d\u0645}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms new coronavirus case, recovery of 17 others |url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=j3upWja115452397665aj3upWj|publisher=WAFA|date=March 20, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''21 March'''\n*Mai Kaileh confirmed four new cases bringing the total to 52. Three of the new cases were students from Ramallah returning from the [[United Kingdom]] and the fourth was a physician from [[Hebron]] who contracted the disease while working at the Israeli [[Hadassah Medical Center|Hadassah Ein Karem]] hospital.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health minister confirms 4 new cases of coronavirus in Palestine, total 52, including 17 cured|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=D2cVLDa115459059936aD2cVLD|publisher=WAFA|date=March 21, 2020 |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n*On 21 March, Palestinian sources confirmed the first two cases in [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]], which originated from Pakistan; the two Palestinians had traveled from Pakistan and had entered Gaza through [[Egypt]]. Once they had tested positive for the virus and they were placed in [[quarantine]] in [[Rafah]] since their arrival on 19 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=First coronavirus cases confirmed in the Palestinian Gaza Strip|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-corona-palestinians-gaza/first-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-the-palestinian-gaza-strip-idUSKBN219004|date=March 22, 2019 |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/palestinians-announce-first-two-cases-of-coronavirus-in-gaza-strip/|title=Palestinians announce first two cases of coronavirus in Gaza Strip|date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020|publisher=Times of Israel}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/latest-on-coronavirus-outbreak/palestinians-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases-in-gaza/1774636|title=Palestinians confirm first coronavirus cases in Gaza|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*The Palestinian Health Ministry said that 53 cases have been confirmed in the West Bank.\n\n'''22 March'''\n*The spokesman for the Palestinian government updated the total number of cases in Palestine to 59 including the 2 cases in Gaza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Six new coronavirus cases in Palestine |url=http://english.pnn.ps/2020/03/22/six-new-coronavirus-cases-in-palestine/|date=March 22, 2020 |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) Update 12 occupied Palestinian territory, March 22, 2020 |url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=645765C60718B88A2540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=3 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403003222/https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=645765C60718B88A2540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0 |archivedate=3 April 2020 |date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*The Palestine News Network said that newspaper ''[[Yediot Aharonot]]'' reported a [[World Health Organization|WHO]] delegation arriving in Gaza via the [[Beit Hanoun]] [[Erez]] crossing.<ref>{{cite news |title=WHO delegation arrives in Gaza Strip  |url=http://english.pnn.ps/2020/03/22/who-delegation-arrives-in-gaza-strip/|date=March 22, 2020 |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n*Following a meeting of the National Emergency, Prime Minister Shtayyeh announced a ban for 2 more weeks on movement between and inside of Palestinian cities for two weeks as of 10:00 PM with the exception of health facilities, pharmacies, bakeries, and grocery stores.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine PM bans movement between and inside of cities|url=http://english.pnn.ps/2020/03/22/palestine-pm-bans-movement-between-and-inside-of-cities/|publisher=PNN|date=March 22, 2020 |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''23 March'''\n*The state-run Qatari Committee to Rebuild Gaza announced on Twitter that it will send $150 million in aid over a six-month period to support [[United Nations]] humanitarian programmes and efforts to help combat the new coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar donating $150mn to support Gaza's coronavirus battle |url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200323-qatar-donating-150mn-to-support-gazas-coronavirus-battle/|publisher=MEMO|date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar announces $150 million aid to Gaza to support U.N. programs, efforts to contain coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-qatar/qatar-announces-150-million-aid-to-gaza-to-support-u-n-programs-efforts-to-contain-coronavirus-idUSKBN21A0TP/|publisher=Reuters|date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''24 March'''\n[[File:COVID-19, Qusin 001.jpg|thumb|Workers at a quarantine site in [[Qusin]].]]\n\n*The daily briefing confirmed the 60th case in Ramallah, who was a woman in her forties returning from the United States, and was immediately quarantined. A person who was previously reported as recovered was found on later testing to still have the disease.<ref>{{cite news |title=New case of coronavirus in Palestine brings total to 60 \u2013 spokesman\n|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=j9FU8wa115495226550aj9FU8w|publisher=WAFA|date=March 24, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=FEB54C9F4C307DFB2540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 13, issued March 24, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n\n'''25 March'''\n[[File:COVID-19, Nablus 002.jpg|thumb|Amman Street in the city of [[Nablus]] is empty due to the mandatory quarantine in Palestine.]]\n\n*The daily briefing confirmed a rise to 62 cases with one being the daughter of the woman who had returned from the US and had tested positive on 24 March and the other being a 62-year-old woman from a village near Ramallah.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two Palestinians tested positive of coronavirus in West Bank; total 62 in Palestine|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=ZgXQPLa115512358104aZgXQPL|publisher=WAFA|date=March 25, 2020 |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n*Reporting the first fatality in the country, a woman aged 60 died.<ref name=\"haaretz1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-palestinians-see-workers-in-israel-settlements-spreading-corona-1.8719556 |title=With 205 respirators, Palestinian Authority fears collapse amid coronavirus outbreak - Israel News |publisher=Haaretz.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> Ibrahim Melhem said \"The woman had experienced symptoms and was later hospitalized\" before succumbing to the illness. The woman was from [[Biddu, Jerusalem|Biddu]], north of Jerusalem and southwest of Ramallah. There are now 62 confirmed cases in the West Bank and two in the Gaza Strip. The two new cases are for the dead woman's son, 46, and his wife, 41.<ref>{{cite news |title=First corona-related death in Palestine; two more cases bring total to 64|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=Wk5B7fa115521875634aWk5B7f|publisher=WAFA|date=March 25, 2020 |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Palestinians report first death from coronavirus|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-palestinians/palestinians-report-first-death-from-coronavirus-idUSKBN21C2U9?|publisher=Reuters|date=March 25, 2020 |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n*Israel is set to release two out of four Palestinian prisoners in the evening, (both Nablus residents), who have been under quarantine in the [[Ramla]] Prison Clinic for ten days as a precautionary measure on suspicion of contracting the virus after coming into contact with an ill Israeli prison officer. The prisoners are to be delivered to Palestinian medics at [[Beit Sira]] military checkpoint, west of Ramallah city.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israel to release two of four prisoners exposed to coronavirus|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=7BnVLLa115518068622a7BnVLL|publisher=WAFA|date=March 25, 2020 |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''26 March'''\n*Ibrahim Milhem confirmed 13 new cases in the village of Biddu bringing the total in Palestine to 86. Tests on people who had been in contact with the woman who died on 25 March confirmed 13 new cases, bringing the total in that village to 18. Of the 86 cases, 9 are in Gaza, including seven who were confirmed positive earlier in the day and who had who came in contact at the Gaza quarantine center with the two confirmed cases held there. 17 cases in Bethlehem have recovered and have been sent to home quarantine for 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |title=13 new cases of coronavirus confirmed in West Bank village bringing total in Palestine to 86|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=PfiFxea115530441411aPfiFxe/|publisher=WAFA|date=March 26, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''27 March'''\n*Palestine Friday morning confirmed seven new cases, raising the total to 91; 5 were from Biddu and 2 were identified from 227 Palestinian workers who had returned from [[Israeli settlement]]s, a man who worked as a gas station worker in [[Gush Etzion]], north of Bethlehem, and his mother, who worked as a cleaner in a nearby settlement.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms seven new coronavirus cases|\nurl=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=koxoR7a115544717706akoxoR7|publisher=WAFA|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> West Bank hospitals have 205 ventilating machines, and as of this date corona tests had been performed on 5,562 people.<ref name=\"haaretz1\"/>\n\n'''28 March'''\n*The daily briefing confirmed 6 new cases bringing the total to 97. Three cases in [[Artas, Bethlehem|Artas]] included the 62-year-old husband of an infected woman as well as her 19-year-old and 17-year-old nephews and a further case being her sister from Beit Iskaria while two other cases were in Jerusalem area villages \u2013 a 29-year-old man from [[Hizma]] and a woman in her 20s from [[Al-Qubeiba, Jerusalem]] who was infected after socializing with an infected sister in Biddu.<ref>{{cite news |title= Spokesman: Six new cases of coronavirus confirmed in West Bank; total 97 in Palestine|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=8BPe89a115556138742a8BPe89|publisher=WAFA|date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> \n*The National COVID-19 Response Plan specifies a requirement of $120 million over 90 days. On 27 March 2020, the humanitarian clusters released an updated inter-agency multi-sectoral COVID-19 response plan in support of this totaling $34 million over 90 days and forming a part of the global UN appeal launched on 25 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=54E2433B167854FE2540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 15, issued March 28, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n\n'''29 March'''\n*Ibrahim Milhem confirmed seven new cases in the West Bank, bringing the total in Palestine to 104. Six cases were confirmed in the village of [[Qatanna]], northwest of Jerusalem and a woman in her 30's from nearby Al-Qubeiba. <ref>{{cite news|title=Spokesman confirms seven new cases of COVID-19 in West Bank |url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=gOLmFpa115566608025agOLmFp|publisher=WAFA|date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n*Mohammad Shtayyeh announced two more cases in the West Bank, bringing the total to 106. At a press conference in Ramallah he said the two cases were for a Palestinian in the village of Qatanna and another in the Hebron Governorate. Additionally, Shtayyeh gave a government estimate of 12 cases among the Palestinian population of [[East Jerusalem]] and currently being treated in Israeli hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Premier declares two more cases of COVID-19 in Palestine|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=JiRdGKa115571366790aJiRdGK|publisher=WAFA|date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n*Two new cases in the West Bank bring the total in Palestine to 108, said Mohammad Milhem. The two new cases are the husband and the son of a woman in Hebron diagnosed earlier with the disease. Two more people recovered in Bethlehem bringing total recoveries to 20, all of whom, bar one, were among the first to get the disease in Bethlehem.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two new cases of coronavirus bring total in Palestine to 108|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=uXSHfJa115576125555auXSHfJ|publisher=WAFA|date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''30 March'''\n[[File:COVID-19, Salfit 001.jpg|thumb|Al-Mad\u012bnah al-Munawwarah Street in [[Salfit]] is empty due to the outbreak in Palestine.]]\n\n*Ibrahim Melhem confirmed 7 new cases in Qatanna bringing the total number of cases to 115.<ref>{{cite news |title=115 COVID-19 cases in Palestine|url= http://english.pnn.ps/2020/03/30/109-covid-19-cases-in-palestine/|publisher=PNN|date=March 30, 2020 |access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n*In Gaza, more than 1760 people are in one of 25 designated quarantine facilities including at Rafah crossing quarantine centre or designated quarantine facilities. The quarantine period will be extended from two to three weeks (21 days). Those coming from crossings at Rafah or [[Erez Crossing|Erez]] have been quarantined since March 15. \n**Home quarantine ended on 26 March for those who entered Gaza 14 days prior. \n*The Ministry of Health limited public primary healthcare service delivery to 14 centers distributed across the five governorates, providing essential services only.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=0F7F4F328EA22F6C2540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 16, issued March 30, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n\n'''31 March'''\n*Ibrahim Melhem confirmed 2 new cases, one in Ramallah and the second a man who returned to the Gaza Strip last week through the Rafah crossing and was placed in confinement since then. This brings the total number of cases to 117 of which 10 are in Gaza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two new corona cases confirmed, one in Ramallah and another in Gaza; total 117|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=BYrM5Ya115595160615aBYrM5Y/|publisher=WAFA|date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\n'''1 April'''\n\n*Fifteen new cases were confirmed in the West Bank today and 2 more in Gaza, bringing total in West Bank to 122 and in Palestine in general to 134, according to government spokesman Mohammad Milhem. The 15 were Palestinians who worked at a poultry factory in the [[Atarot]] industrial area of East Jerusalem. Milhem said Israel had communicated the possibility of the workers being infected and that although nine of the infected workers who were in one bus were taken straight from the factory to quarantine centers in Ramallah, the rest crossed Israeli military checkpoints, went to their villages and mingled with people before they were detected, which could raise the number of infected once tests are conducted.<ref>{{cite news |title=15 new cases of coronavirus cased in West Bank brings up total in Palestine to 134|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=07SXt8a115616099181a07SXt8|publisher=WAFA|date=April 1, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=C5DDEFA7A12C36B32540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 17, issued April 1, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n\n*Israel has linked possible assistance for Gaza's efforts to combat the disease to progress in Israel's recovering the remains of two soldiers killed in the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|2014 war]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Israel links coronavirus aid for Gaza to recovering soldiers\n|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-israel-gaza/israel-links-coronavirus-aid-for-gaza-to-recovering-soldiers-idUSKBN21J5ZC?|publisher=Reuters|date=April 1, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n'''2 April'''\n*Palestinian Health Ministry spokesman Kamal Shakhra confirmed 21 new cases bringing the total to 155, most of the cases being Palestinians who worked in Israel and returned home along with those who were in contact with them. 20 were from the Ramallah and Jerusalem-area villages and one in Hebron. Workers returning home this week while Israel celebrates Passover were asked to isolate themselves at their homes for two weeks. The Health Ministry plans to check an estimated 60,000 workers as they return.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health Ministry: 21 new coronavirus cases confirmed in Palestine; total 155|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=BznfYEa115628471970aBznfYE|publisher=WAFA|date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[UNWRA|The United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East]] resumed the distribution of food aid in the Gaza Strip on 31 March. Food baskets are now delivered directly to beneficiaries\u2019 homes as a precautionary measure by UNRWA, to prevent gatherings as part of its steps to reduce and prevent the spread of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=UNRWA distributes food aid to families in Gaza|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200402-unrwa-distributes-food-aid-to-families-in-gaza/|publisher=MEMO|date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n*The number of confirmed cases rose to 161, five of them related to the Atarot poultry farm where 250 Palestinian workers who work there have yet to be tested plus one other in Beitunia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms five new coronavirus cases|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=WErQZBa115635134241aWErQZB|publisher=WAFA|date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms new coronavirus case|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=cV3Tc4a115642748265acV3Tc4|publisher=WAFA|date=April 3, 2020 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''3 April'''\n\n*Ibrahim Milhem announced ten new cases bringing the total to 171, residents of Biddu, Qatanna, [[Hizma]] and Tulkarem. Test results for the 250 Palestinian workers from the Atarot poultry plant are due later.<ref>{{cite news|title=PalCOVID-19 cases in Palestine rise to 171|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=cV3Tc4a115643700018acV3Tc4|publisher=WAFA|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404033130/http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=cV3Tc4a115643700018acV3Tc4|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*President Abbas declared a State of Emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=0BC8EC6C6F19B9312540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 18, issued April 3, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n*Prime Minister Mohammad Shtayyeh confirmed another 22 cases that brings the total to 193. The Prime Minister stressed that the next two weeks will be difficult as around 45,000 Palestinian workers in Israel return from their workplace in Israel. Shtayyeh added, \"We are trying hard to arrange the return of the workers with the Israeli side so that we can take the necessary health measures. We hope that Israel will agree to this, as this virus is the enemy of all mankind and knows no borders, gender or religion,\" he said. \"We also asked Israel to check the workers prior to their arrival.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Premier confirms 22 more cases of COVID-19 bring total up to 193|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=DMes5Ra115649410536aDMes5R|publisher=WAFA|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404033238/http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=DMes5Ra115649410536aDMes5R|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n'''4 April'''\n\n*Kamal Shakhra confirmed 11 new cases of coronavirus which together with the case from Halhoul raised the total to 205. All but three were Palestinian workers in a poultry factory in [[Lod]] apparently owned by the same person as the Atarot poultry factory. Three cases were in [[Beitunia]], three in Qatanna, one in [[Beit 'Anan]], two in Tulkarm refugee camp and two were in [[Surif]]. Out of the 205 cases, 12 are located in Gaza, among whom three have recovered.<ref>{{cite news |title=Around midnight, government confirms new coronavirus case in a West Bank town; total 194|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=g3S5goa115652265795ag3S5go|publisher=WAFA|date=April 4, 2020 |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Health Ministry announces 11 new cases of coronavirus in Palestine; total 205|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=PsrGN5a115657024560aPsrGN5|publisher=WAFA|date=April 4, 2020 |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n*Ibrahim Milhem confirmed 5 more cases and at the evening briefing, Kamal Shakhra confirmed a further 6 cases for a total of 216. The five cases were three from Halhul, the fourth case was from nearby Yatta and the fifth from Qarawat Bani Zaid. The additional six cases were reported in the governorates of Jerusalem, Bethlehem, and Ramallah. The rapid increase in cases is attributed to the gradual return of Palestinian workers in Israel and Israeli settlements to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Government confirms 5 more cases of Covid-19, total hits 210|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=6itoH1a115660831572a6itoH1|publisher=WAFA|date=April 4, 2020 |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Official confirms 6 more cases of Covid-19 in West Bank|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=6itoH1a115661783325a6itoH1|publisher=WAFA|date=April 4, 2020 |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n'''5 April'''\n\n*Kamal Shakhra confirmed nine  more cases bringing the total to 226. The nine cases were reported in the governorates of Ramallah, Jenin, and Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite news |title=Official confirms nine more cases of COVID-19, total hits 226|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=4n923va115667493843a4n923v|publisher=WAFA|date=April 5, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>Ibrahim Milhem confirmed two new cases from Bethlehem area villages, six more in Beitunia which now is subject of a total lockdown, a case from the town of Sair and two others in Biddo, bringing the total to 237.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two new cases of coronavirus in West Bank; total 228|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=9zpHgza115671300855a9zpHgz|publisher=WAFA|date=April 5, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Six more coronavirus cases confirmed in West Bank bring total in Palestine to 234|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=nCGCZta115672252608anCGCZt|publisher=WAFA|date=April 5, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Three new coronavirus cases confirmed in West Bank by midnight; total in Palestine 237|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=61U3XMa115674156114a61U3XM|publisher=WAFA|date=April 5, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=3EFD1153EA173C132540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 19, issued April 5, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n\n'''6 April'''\n\n*Kamal Shakhra confirmed 15 new cases for a total 252 cases at the daily briefing following 11 cases from two families in the Biddo, Qatanna and Jdeireh villages. Interior Ministry spokesman Ghassan Nimr said Biddo, Qatanna and Jdeireh villages had 99 cases alone, mainly caused by social visits. He said Bethlehem district had 52 cases and Ramallah district 58 cases, followed by 13 in the Hebron district, and the rest in other West Bank areas.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health Ministry confirms 15 new coronavirus cases in West Bank; total in Palestine 252|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=YOBpjEa115680818385aYOBpjE|publisher=WAFA|date=April 6, 2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*A new total figure of 254 including a new case in Gaza was reported late in the day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Newspapers Review: New coronavirus cases in West Bank and Gaza highlight of dailies|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=j3zZDMa115692239421aj3zZDM|publisher=WAFA|date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''7 April'''\n\n*Kamal Shakhra confirmed 6 more cases bringing the total to 260.<ref>{{cite news |title=Six new cases of coronavirus in West Bank, one in Gaza raise total in Palestine to 260|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=8xddYEa115696046433a8xddYE|publisher=WAFA|date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*Al Quds University President, Professor Imad Abu Kishek announced that his university has \u201csucceeded in producing a fully computerized ventilator capable of saving lives and providing a viable alternative to the shortage in Palestine and beyond in the standard commercial ventilators and other respiratory support machines\u201d. The Palestinian Ministry of Health had reported that only 250 medical ventilators are available throughout all Palestinian hospitals and that two-thirds of these machines are already in use. The ventilators should be ready for production as soon as the Palestinian Standard Institute (PSI) gives its final approval to the prototype.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestinian Ingenuity: Al-Quds University Produces Innovative Prototype for Inexpensive Ventilators|url=https://www.palestinechronicle.com/palestinian-ingenuity-al-quds-university-produces-innovative-prototype-for-inexpensive-ventilators/|publisher=The Palestine Chronicle|date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n'''8 April'''\n\n*The daily briefing confirmed 2 new cases for a total 263. A total of 44 cases have recovered, 36 in the West Bank and eight in Gaza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two new corona cases in Palestine raise total to 263, says health ministry|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=9EhH7Oa115710322728a9EhH7O|publisher=WAFA|date=April 8, 2020 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*The Commissioner-General of the United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA), Philippe Lazzarini and Dr. Mohammad Shtayyeh met by teleconference and discussed the situation of Palestine refugees, particularly in the face of the pandemic. The Commissioner-General updated the Prime Minister on the Agency's prevention and response plans and efforts to raise needed funds. He also briefed the Prime Minister on the situation of Palestinian refugees in [[Jordan]], [[Lebanon]], and [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestinian Prime Minister warns from the possibility of forming Israeli government aimed at annexing the West Bank|url=http://english.pnn.ps/2020/04/08/commissioner-general-of-unrwa-meets-palestinian-prime-minister/|publisher=PNN|date=April 8, 2020 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n'''9 April'''\n\n*At the daily briefing Kamal Shakhra said that there were no new cases and gave a breakdown of the 263 cases to date, being 89 workers in Israel, 103 that were in close contact with infected cases, 29 among travellers, 40 cases that were in contact with the tourists in Bethlehem,1 medical staff and a prisoner. Shakhra said a total of 16,068 tests had been conducted since  March 5.<ref>{{cite news |title=With no new corona cases reported so far, health ministry gives a breakdown of cases|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=LCNJJXa115721743764aLCNJJX|publisher=WAFA|date=April 9, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*Meeting with Mohammed Shtayyeh, the European Union representative, Sven K\u00fchn von Burgsdorff  announced  an assistance package of around \u20ac71 million in response to the Palestinian Authority's COVID-19 Response Plan for dealing with the pandemic including contributing \u20ac9.5 million more to the six East Jerusalem hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |title=EU offers \u20ac71 million in coronavirus aid package to Palestinians|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=vnusQra115725550776avnusQr|publisher=WAFA|date=April 9, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=768827089ACE38A12540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=UPDATED: WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 20, issued April 9, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n\n'''10 April'''\n\n*Ibrahim Milhem confirmed 3 new cases, one from Halhul and two cases from Artas for a total of 266. Recoveries increased to 45, including 9 in Gaza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms three new coronavirus cases|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=pGrgt1a115729357788apGrgt1|publisher=WAFA|date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>He also confirmed a second death, of a resident of Barta\u2019a.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms second coronavirus death & confirms three new cases|url=http://english.pnn.ps/2020/04/10/palestine-confirms-second-coronavirus-death-confirms-three-new-cases/|publisher=PNN|date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*The United Kingdom announced two support packages worth $1m to purchase medical supplies for health systems through UNICEF and WHO.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK SUPPORTS PALESTINIAN EFFORT TO COMBAT CORONAVIRUS|url=http://english.pnn.ps/2020/04/10/uk-supports-palestinian-effort-to-combat-coronavirus/|publisher=PNN|date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*Ibrahim Milhem confirmed a new case in Bani Na'im for a total of 267.<ref>{{cite news |title=Government confirms one more case of COVID-19|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=Bn9DWFa115734116553aBn9DWF|publisher=WAFA|date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n'''11 April'''\n\n*Kamal Shakhra confirmed a new case in Jdeireh for a total of 268 while recovered cases reached 46.<ref>{{cite news |title=A new coronavirus case confirmed in Palestine, raising total to 268|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=JV6qbOa115738875318aJV6qbO|publisher=WAFA|date=April 11, 2020 |access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*The Ministry of Health announced 11 recovered cases, bringing the total number to 57.<ref>{{cite news |title=11 new coronavirus recoveries in West Bank|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=N0iDOMa115746489342aN0iDOM|publisher=WAFA|date=April 11, 2020 |access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''12 April'''\n\n*A Palestinian worker showing coronavirus symptoms was left today by Israeli settlers outside Burkan said Abdullah Kmail, the Governor of Salfit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Settlers dump Palestinian worker with coronavirus symptoms|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=wxY8KYa115756006872awxY8KY|publisher=WAFA|date=April 12, 2020 |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=8B6386DE30945DF12540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 21, issued April 12, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n'''13 April'''\n\n*Ibrahim Milhem confirmed three cases, two overnight from Hebron and another from Rafat for a total 272 while recoveries rose to 59. He also said there were unconfirmed 36 corona cases in occupied East Jerusalem, which would bring the total in all the occupied Palestinian territories to 308.<ref>{{cite news |title= One new coronavirus case confirmed in West Bank; total in Palestine 272|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=SD6spXa115764572649aSD6spX|publisher=WAFA|date=April 13, 2020 |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Two new coronavirus cases confirmed in West Bank overnight, total 271, one recovered|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=QmzBOQa115761717390aQmzBOQ|publisher=WAFA|date=April 13, 2020 |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''14 April'''\n\n*Kamal Shakhra confirmed 10 new cases for a total of 284, 5 from Izzarieh, 3 from Rafat and 1 each from Jenin and Hebron with recoveries rising to 64.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health Ministry: 10 new coronavirus cases confirmed in West Bank; total in Palestine 284|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=Dxzztia115783607709aDxzzti|publisher=WAFA|date=April 14, 2020 |access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*In East Jerusalem, medical professionals estimate that at least 80 patients have been diagnosed. Half the patients are said to be in Silwan. On 12 April, three cases were identified in Issawiya, two of whom work in the health system and in nursing homes, and the first patient was identified in Shoafat refugee camp. In response to increasing concern, the government announced that three more testing clinics would open in East Jerusalem, in Silwan, in Kafr Aqab and in Shoafat refugee camp.<ref>{{cite news |title=After Weeks of Warning, Coronavirus Spreading Among Palestinians in East Jerusalem|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/palestinians/.premium-after-weeks-of-warning-coronavirus-spreading-among-palestinians-in-east-jerusalem-1.8765534|publisher=Haaretz|date=April 14, 2020 |access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n*At the evening briefing,Ibrahim Milhem confirmed 3 more cases bringing the total to 287.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms three new coronavirus cases|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=cCRLosa115790269980acCRLos|publisher=WAFA|date=April 14, 2020 |access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n'''15 April'''\n\n*Minister of Health Mai Alkaila confirmed 3 new cases in the West Bank today. Together with a new case reported late yesterday in Kharbatha al-Misbah this raised the total cases to 291. The three cases were medics apparently infected while working at Augusta Victoria hospital in East Jerusalem. Alkaila also said that it is believed there are 78 positive corona cases in  East Jerusalem although this cannot be confirmed as Israel does not report the figure.<ref>{{cite news |title=New coronavirus case in West Bank last night raises total to 288|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=3jFqTQa115794076992a3jFqTQ|publisher=WAFA|date=April 15, 2020 |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Three new coronavirus cases in West Bank raise total to 291|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=dTxTvSa115800739263adTxTvS|publisher=WAFA|date=April 15, 2020 |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*A testing clinic in Silwan was closed down because the kits were supplied by the Palestinian Authority and Israel prohibits PA activity in Jerusalem. The Israeli Health Ministry recently opened a testing clinic in Silwan but it is only accessible to members of the Clalit health maintenance organization.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israeli Police Raid Palestinian Coronavirus Testing Clinic in East Jerusalem |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israeli-police-raid-palestinian-coronavirus-testing-clinic-in-east-jerusalem-1.8767788|publisher=Haaretz|date=April 15, 2020 |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n*Three new cases were confirmed including one from Bethlehem area who had previously recovered, bringing the total to 293. It is thought that there are 81  cases in East Jerusalem after 3 new cases were reported in Jabal al-Mukabber.<ref>{{cite news |title=Three new coronavirus cases in West Bank last night, one relapsed after recovering; total 293\n|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=dHgQuPa115812160299adHgQuP|publisher=WAFA|date=April 16, 2020 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''16 April'''\n\n*Mai Alkaila confirmed a new case bringing the total to 294. The three new cases late yesterday were for two medics from Dheisheh refugee camp and from Obeidieh and the third a man from Kharbatha al-Misbah.<ref>{{cite news |title=One new coronavirus case in West Bank brings total in Palestine to 294|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=dHgQuPa115814063805adHgQuP|publisher=WAFA|date=April 16, 2020 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=117119863068D0132540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 22, issued April 16, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n\n*The United States announced $5 million in aid \"to meet immediate, life-saving needs in combating COVID-19,\" ending a two-year freeze of aid funds.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Announces $5m Coronavirus Grant to Palestinians After a Two-year Freeze of Aid |url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-u-s-announces-5m-coronavirus-grant-to-palestinians-after-a-two-year-freeze-of-aid-1.8775618|publisher=Haaretz|date=April 16, 2020 |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''17 April'''\n\n*Mai Alkaila confirmed 12 new cases bringing the total to 307 while there are thought to be 95 cases in East Jerusalem.The new cases are Palestinians working in Israel who had just returned home from their workplace or those who came in contact with them and came from Hebron, Ramallah, Jenin, Jerusalem, and Bethlehem. Another case was previously diagnosed in Bani Na'im. With eight recoveries in Ramallah, the total rose to 69.<ref>{{cite news |title=Government confirms one more case of coronavirus |url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=2yufCma115820726076a2yufCm|publisher=WAFA|date=April 17, 2020 |access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Health Minister confirms 12 more cases of coronavirus|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=x8Uv2ya115826436594ax8Uv2y|publisher=WAFA|date=April 17, 2020 |access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*The UN Chief Antonio Guterres said that he asked the UN Special Coordinator for the Middle East Peace Process, Nikolay Mladenov, to work with Israeli officials to ensure the protection of the Palestinian detainees in Israeli prisons.<ref>{{cite news |title=UN chief urges protection of Palestinian detainees from coronavirus infection|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=9D1i6Ea115825484841a9D1i6E|publisher=WAFA|date=April 17, 2020 |access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n'''18 April'''\n\n*Mai Alkaila confirmed 6 new cases raising the total to 313. She also confirmed that a 78-year-old Palestinian from Issawiya died, the first victim in East Jerusalem, where there are thought to be 105 cases.<ref>{{cite web|title=Palestinian woman dies in occupied East Jerusalem of coronavirus; 6 new cases in West Bank|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=VDPNx5a115835954124aVDPNx5/|publisher =WAFA|date=April 18, 2020|access-date = April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n'''19 April'''\n\n*Six new cases were confirmed raising the total to 320, Mai Alkaila said today. The six new cases were of a woman from the Shuqba, 4 cases for four sisters from Kafr Aqab and a sixth case in Tulkarm.<ref>{{cite web|title=Health Minister confirms 6 new COVID-19 cases in West Bank|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=E2Y2O7a115843568148aE2Y2O7|publisher =WAFA|date=April 19, 2020|access-date = April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://who18.createsend.com/campaigns/reports/viewCampaign.aspx?d=j&c=99FA4938D049E3A8&ID=2C14C0610A6B4C9C2540EF23F30FEDED&temp=False&tx=0&source=Report|title=WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) Update 23, issued April 19, 2020 &#124; Campaign Monitor|website=who18.createsend.com}}</ref>\n\n*Ibrahim Milhem confirmed an additional two new cases in Yatta bringing the total to 322.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two more cases of COVID-19 confirmed in West Bank|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=1MTXO3a115847375160a1MTXO3|publisher=WAFA|date=April 19, 2020 |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n'''20 April'''\n\n*Kamal Shakhra confirmed 7 new cases including 2 in Gaza for a total of 329.The cases include two from Beit Anan, two from Kafr Aqab and one from Nablus. Shakhra also said two people from Bethlehem who had recently recovered had once again tested positive for the disease, putting the total of recovered now at 69, including 11 in Gaza. There are thought to be 120 cases in East Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ministry of Health: Seven new cases of coronavirus in Palestine for a total of 329|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=WVgTR9a115852133925aWVgTR9|publisher=WAFA|date=April 20, 2020 |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''21 April'''\n\n*Mai Alkaila confirmed no new cases were reported in the West Bank and Gaza Strip in the last 24 hours. All the patients at corona centers are in good health and no one is currently in ICU. There are thought to be 132 cases in East Jerusalem and two Palestinians have also died there. A total of 25,000 corona tests were conducted so far and the health ministry in now in a position to do 4000 tests a day.<ref>{{cite news |title=With no new corona cases reported in last 24 hours, over 11,500 remain in quarantine: minister\n|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=NKesdra115868313726aNKesdr|publisher=WAFA|date=April 21, 2020 |access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*The Health Ministry confirmed this evening five new cases, raising the total number of confirmed cases to 334, including three Palestinians from Kafr Aqab and two others from Gaza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Palestine confirms five new coronavirus cases|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=5hoCPHa115874024244a5hoCPH|publisher=WAFA|date=April 21, 2020|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''22 April'''\n\n*Mai Alkaila confirmed a new case in Kafr Aqab, bringing the total to 335. In addition, there are thought to be another 139 cases in East Jerusalem <ref>{{cite news |title=One coronavirus case confirmed in an East Jerusalem neighborhood - health minister|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=4mqeXba115886397033a4mqeXb|publisher=WAFA|date=April 22, 2020|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*Referring to the April 16 announcement of $5 million in aid from the U.S., Salman al-Harfi, the Palestinian envoy to France said that Palestinian hospitals have yet to see any of the aid funds and went on to say $3.5 million had been allocated to non-governmental organizations friendly with Washington but provided no further details.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u2018We did not get a cent\u2019: Palestinian diplomat says US \u2018lying\u2019 about promised $5mn aid package to hospitals facing Covid-19 |url=https://www.rt.com/news/486516-us-lied-palestine-aid-ambassador/|publisher=RT|date=April 22, 2020|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n'''23 April'''\n\n*Mai Alkaila confirmed a new case in Dahrieh bringing the total cases to 335. There are also thought to be 144 cases from East Jerusalem neighborhoods inside the [[West Bank barrier]]. Recoveries in the West Bank rose to 74.<ref>{{cite news |title=One new coronavirus case in West Bank, five in East Jerusalem - health minister|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=KkEh1Ya116847667563aKkEh1Y|publisher=WAFA|date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Outbreaks==\n=== Bethlehem ===\nThe city of Bethlehem became the first to experience an outbreak with confirmed cases on early March. The City of Bethlehem was locked down on March 7th as 16 cases of infection were found in the West Bank, including nine cases in Bethlehem.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Palestinian refugee camps ===\nThe crowded [[Palestinian refugee camps]] face a grave threat if coronavirus spreads.<ref>{{cite news |title=Packed with refugees, Palestinian camps face grave threat if coronavirus spreads|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-palestinians-camps/packed-with-refugees-palestinian-camps-face-grave-threat-if-coronavirus-spreads-idUSKBN21K1BC|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=April 4, 2020 |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> On 22 April, a [[Palestinians in Syria|Palestinian from Syria]] became the first case reported in a [[refugee camp]], located in the [[Wavel]] refugee camp in [[Beqaa Governorate|Bekaa]], Lebanon.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karam|first=Zeina|url=https://apnews.com/14b031bac52e45dfebda490fd8351619|title=First virus case recorded in refugee camp in Lebanon|date=22 Apr 2020|work=[[Associated Press]] News|access-date=22 Apr 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rummler|first=Orion|url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-refugees-lebanon-palestine-48ef93c3-2d88-4acf-b9a0-1763ebd67073.html|title=Palestinian refugee camp in Lebanon reports first coronavirus case|date=22 Apr 2020|work=[[Axios]]|access-date=22 Apr 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Palestinians abroad==\n\nThe Foreign Affairs and Expatriates Ministry announced 500 cases and 23 deaths among [[Palestinian diaspora|Palestinians in the diaspora]], including 349 cases and 15 deaths in the United States. The ministry noted that around 1,000 Palestinian doctors were participating in health efforts in Europe along with hundreds more in the [[US]], [[Venezuela]] and [[Cuba]] among other states. Four doctors were declared dead after contracting coronavirus; one in [[New Jersey]], two in Spain and one in [[Italy]], while some 20 American doctors and paramedics tested positive for the virus in New Jersey.<ref>{{cite news |title=Foreign Ministry: 500 confirmed coronavirus cases, 23 deaths in diaspora|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=0vMZsda115715081493a0vMZsd|publisher=WAFA|date=April 8, 2020 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Palestinian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Expatriates updated to 678 cases and 30 deaths, 437 and 22 respectively being in the U.S., 3 in Spain and one each in Italy, the [[Netherlands]], [[Austria]], [[Algeria]] and [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Foreign Ministry: 30 deaths, 678 cases of coronavirus among Palestinians in the diaspora|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=cDiVJ0a115768379661acDiVJ0|publisher=WAFA|date=April 13, 2020 |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Palestinian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Expatriates announced on April 23 the first death among the Palestinian community in the United Kingdom raising the number of diaspora Palestinians worldwide who died from the disease to 49. The overall number of cases among diaspora Palestinians rose to 1042 with the majority of cases and deaths being in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=First death from coronavirus among the Palestinian community in UK|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=QKVZxga116856233340aQKVZxg|publisher=WAFA|date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Palestine}}\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Jordan]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.emro.who.int/pse/palestine-news/landing-page-for-covid19.html WHO oPT updates]\n*[http://corona.ps/ Palestinian official website for cases]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the State of Palestine| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in the State of Palestine|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Palestine]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Palestine]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the State of Palestine]]\n[[Category:Health in the State of Palestine]]\n", "name_user": "Selfstudier", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePalestinians abroad:Use FAE as an abbreviation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_State_of_Palestine"}
{"title_page": "Sathya Sai Baba", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian guru}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox Hindu leader\n|name              = Sathya Sai Baba\n|image             = Bhagawan_Sri_Sathya_Sai_Baba.jpg\n|alt               =\n|caption           =\n| religion = [[Hinduism]]\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date|1926|11|23|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Puttaparthi]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n|death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2011|4|24|1926|11|23}}\n|death_place       = Puttaparthi, [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]]\n|birth_name        = Sathyanarayana Raju\n|founder           = [[Sathya Sai Organization]] \n|guru              = <!-- The teacher (if any) -->\n|philosophy        = Love all. Serve all.\nHelp Ever. Hurt Never.\n|nationality       = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n|signature         =\n}}\n{{Hindu philosophy}} \n'''Sathya Sai Baba''' (born '''Sathyanarayana Raju'''; 23 November 1926{{spaced ndash}}24 April 2011<ref name=\"BBC obit\">{{cite news |publisher=BBC| title=Obituary: Indian guru Sai Baba |date= 24 April 2011|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13153536 |quote=Satya Sai Baba was born Sathyanarayana Raju on 23 November 1926}}</ref>) was an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Tantra|guru]] and philanthropist.<ref name=\"babb83\">{{cite journal|last1=Babb|first1=Lawrence A.|title=Sathya Sai Baba's Magic|journal=Anthropological Quarterly|date=1983|volume=56|issue=3|pages=116\u2013124|doi=10.2307/3317305|jstor=3317305}}</ref><ref name=\"das15\">{{cite journal|last1=Das|first1=M. K.|title=Televising religion: A study of Sathya Sai Baba's funeral broadcast in Gangtok, India|journal=Anthropological Notebooks|date=2015|volume=21|issue=3|pages=83\u2013104|url=http://www.drustvo-antropologov.si/AN/PDF/2015_3/Anthropological_Notebooks_XXI_3_Kumar%20Das.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"RichardWeiss\">{{cite journal|last1=Weiss|first1=Richard|date=December 2005|title=THE GLOBAL GURU: SAI BABA AND THE MIRACLE OF THE MODERN|url=http://www.nzasia.org.nz/downloads/NZJAS-Dec05/7_2_2.pdf|journal=New Zealand Journal of Asian Studies|volume=7|issue=2|pages=5\u201319}}</ref> At the age of fourteen he claimed that he was the [[reincarnation]] of [[Sai Baba of Shirdi|Shirdi Sai Baba]],<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\" /><ref name=\"kent\" /> and encouraged his followers to believe the same.<ref name=\"Singleton, Mark| Goldberg, Ellen\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GSpnAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT208&dq=sai+baba+god+incarnate+academic+studies#v=onepage&q=sai%20baba%20god%20incarnate%20academic%20studies&f=false|title=Gurus of Modern Yoga|isbn=9780199374953|last1=Singleton|first1=Mark|last2=Goldberg|first2=Ellen|date=27 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"BabbLawrence\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Redemptive_Encounters.html?id=B8bMjUt6AqIC|title=Redemptive Encounters: Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition|last=Babb|first=Lawrence A.|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=1991|isbn=978-0-520-07636-5|location=|page=164}}</ref>\n\nSathya Sai Baba's purported [[Materialization (parapsychology)|materialisations]] of ''[[Vibhuti#Sacred ash|vibhuti]]'' (holy ash) and other small objects such as rings, necklaces, and watches, were a source of controversy.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/this_world/3813469.stm|title=Sai Baba: God-man or con man?|last=Datta|first=Tanya|date=17 June 2004|work=BBC News}}</ref> Some have analyzed them as being mere [[sleight of hand|sleights of hand]]; while his followers have considered them as signs of his divinity.<ref name=\"quack\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=55wFpydSZ8oC&pg=PA120|title=Disenchanting India: Organized Rationalism and Criticism of Religion in India|author=Johannes Quack|date=22 November 2011|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-981260-8|location=|pages=120}}</ref><ref name=\"CNNSingh\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/04/24/india.spiritual.guru.death/|title=Indian spiritual guru dies at 85|author=Harmeet Shah Singh|date=24 April 2011|newspaper=CNN|accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref> Reports of [[faith healing]]s have been attributed to Sathya Sai Baba by his followers.<ref name=\"Palmer116\">Palmer, Norris W. \"Baba's World\". In: {{cite book|title=Gurus in America|last=Forsthoefel|first=Thomas A.|last2=Humes|first2=Cynthia Ann (eds.)|publisher=State University of New York Press|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7914-6574-5|place=Albany, NY|author-link=|author2-link=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Modern Miracles: Sathya Sai Baba The Story of a Modern Day Prophet|last=Haraldsson Ph.D|first=Erlendur|publisher=Rider|year=1987|isbn=978-1-908733-25-2|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sathya Sai Organisation]], founded by Sathya Sai Baba \"to enable its members to undertake service activities as a means to spiritual advancement\",<ref name=\"srisaiorg\"/> has over 1,200 Sathya Sai Centres (branches) in 126 countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Branches|url=http://www.sathyasai.org/organize/content.htm|publisher=Official website \u2013 International Sai Organisation|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref> Through this organisation, Sathya Sai Baba established a network of free hospitals, clinics, drinking water projects, auditoriums, [[ashram]]s and schools.<ref name=funeral>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13204914|title=Thousands flock to funeral of India guru Satya Sai Baba|work=BBC News|date=27 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=deccanheraldlegacy>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/156315/sai-babas-legacy.html|title=Sai Baba's legacy|work=Deccan Herald|date=2011-04-24}}</ref><ref name=\"toigovernments\">{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-25/india/29470992_1_sathya-sai-baba-whitefield-ashram-god | work=The Times Of India | title='Sai Baba did everything govt could not' \u2013 The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n===Early life===\n\nAlmost everything known about Sathya Sai Baba's early life stems from the [[hagiography]] that grew around him, narratives that hold special meaning to his devotees and are considered by them to be evidence of his divine nature.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/><ref name=\"UrbanHugh74\" /><ref name=\"Palmer99\">{{cite book|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/4991|title=Gurus in America|last=Palmer|first=Norris W.|publisher=[[State University of New York Press]]|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7914-6574-5|editor-last=A. Forsthoefel|editor-first=Thomas|place=Albany, NY|page=99|chapter=Baba\u2019s World: A Global Guru and His Movement|editor-last2=Ann Humes|editor-first2=Cynthia|chapter-url=https://muse.jhu.edu/chapter/116246}}</ref> According to these sources, Sathya Narayana Raju was born to Meesaraganda Easwaramma and Peddavenkama Raju Ratnakaram in the village of [[Puttaparthi]], to a [[Bhatraju]] family,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/south/story/a-phenomenon-called-sathya-sai-baba-132676-2011-04-25|title=A phenomenon called Sathya Sai Baba|last=Rao|first=A. Srinivasa|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=6fHFLQDOEuYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=bhat%20raju&f=false|title=Winged Faith: Rethinking Globalization and Religious Pluralism through the Sathya Sai Movement|last=Srinivas|first=Tulasi|date=2010-06-10|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-52052-2|location=|pages=54|language=en}}</ref> an [[Other Backward Class|OBC]] community of religious musicians and balladeers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/35458340.pdf|title=Sathya Sai Baba as Avatar: \"His Story\" and the History of an Idea|last=Spurr|first=Michael James|date=|website=University of Canterbury|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GSpnAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT368&dq=Bhatraju#v=onepage&q=Bhat%20raju&f=false|title=Gurus of Modern Yoga|last=Singleton|first=Mark|last2=Goldberg|first2=Ellen|date=2013-11-27|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-937495-3|language=en}}</ref> in what was the [[Madras Presidency]] of [[British Raj|British India]].<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/><ref>Haraldsson, Erlendur, Miracles are my visiting cards \u2013 An investigative inquiry on Sathya Sai Baba, (1997 revised and updated edition published by Sai Towers, Prasanthi Nilayam, India), p. 55, {{ISBN|81-86822-32-1}}</ref><ref name=\"Eade\">{{Cite book|date=2002-01-01|editor-last=Eade|editor-first=John|editor2-last=Mele|editor2-first=Christopher|title=Understanding the City|publisher=Wiley|language=en|doi=10.1002/9780470693582|isbn=9780470693582}}</ref> His birth was alleged by his mother Easwaramma to be of a [[Miraculous births|miraculous conception]].<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/><ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/>\n\nSathya Sai Baba's siblings included elder brother Ratnakaram Seshama Raju (1911\u20131985), sisters Venkamma (1918\u20131993) and Parvathamma (1920\u20131998), and younger brother Janakiramaiah (1931\u20132003).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-22/india/29463028_1_sathya-sai-baba-satyajit-trust-affairsnephew|title=Vaastu dosham at hospital he built, say Sai kin|last=|first=|date=25 April 2011|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs a child, he was described as \"unusually intelligent\" and charitable, though not necessarily academically inclined, as his interests were of a more spiritual nature.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/><ref name=Palmer99 /> He was uncommonly talented in devotional music, dance and drama.<ref name=Palmer99 /><ref name=\"kent\">{{cite book | last = Kent | first = Alexandra | authorlink = |title =Divinity and Diversity: A Hindu Revitalization Movement in Malaysia |publisher = Nordic Institute of Asian Studies | year = 2005  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=26sVhUo_aM4C&pg=PA37 |pages = 37\u201339| isbn = 978-87-91114-40-3}}</ref> From a young age, he has been alleged to have been capable of materialising objects such as food and sweets out of thin air.<ref name=\"AlexandraKent\">{{Cite journal|last=Kent|first=Alexandra|date=2000-01-01|title=Creating Divine Unity: Chinese Recruitment in the Sathya Sai Baba Movement of Malaysia|journal=Journal of Contemporary Religion|volume=15|issue=1|pages=5\u201327|doi=10.1080/135379000112116|issn=1353-7903}}</ref>\n\n===Proclamation===\n\n[[File:Baba-1940's.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Sai Baba at the age of 14, soon after proclaiming he was the reincarnation of Shirdi Sai Baba]]\nOn 8 March 1940, while living with his elder brother Seshama Raju in [[Uravakonda]], a small town near Puttaparthi, 14 year old Sathya was apparently stung by a scorpion.<ref name=\"AlexandraKent\"/> He lost consciousness for several hours<ref name=\"kent\"/> and in the next few days underwent a noticeable change in behaviour. There were \"symptoms of laughing and weeping, eloquence and silence.\" It is claimed that then \"he began to sing [[Sanskrit]] verses, a language of which it is alleged he had no prior knowledge.\"<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/> Doctors concluded his behaviour to be [[hysteria]].<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/> Concerned, his parents brought Sathya back home to Puttaparthi and took him to many priests, doctors and exorcists. One of the exorcists at [[Kadiri]], a town near Puttaparthi, went to the extent of torturing him with the aim of curing him; Sathya seemingly kept calm throughout the torture.\n\nOn 23 May 1940, Sathya called household members and reportedly materialised sugar candy (''[[prasad]])'' and flowers for them. His father became furious at seeing this, thinking his son was [[Spirit possession|bewitched]]. He took a stick and threatened to beat him if Sathya did not reveal who he really was, the young Sathya responded calmly and firmly \"I am Sai Baba\", a reference to [[Sai Baba of Shirdi]].<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/><ref name=\"kent\"/> This was the first time he proclaimed himself to be the reincarnation of Sai Baba of Shirdi\u2014a saint who became famous in the late 19th and early 20th centuries in [[Maharashtra]] and had died eight years before Sathya was born.<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/>\n\n===First mandir and development of Puttaparthi===\n\nIn 1944, a [[mandir]] for Sai Baba's devotees was built near the village of [[Puttaparthi]]. It is now referred to as the \"old mandir\".<ref name=\"bowen\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Sathya_Sai_Baba_Community_in_Bradfor.html?id=fJwQAAAACAAJ|title=The Sathya Sai Baba Community in Bradford: Its Origin and Development, Religious Beliefs and Practices|last=Bowen|first=David|date=1988|publisher=Department of Theology and Religious Studies, University of Leeds|isbn=9781871363029|language=en}}</ref> The construction of [[Prashanthi Nilayam]], the current ashram, began in 1948 and was completed in 1950.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/><ref name=\"bowen\"/> In 1954, Sai Baba established a small free general hospital in the village of Puttaparthi.<ref name=\"TheHinduNewspaper\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/features/saibaba/stories/2005112300270300.htm |title=Sri Sathya Sai 80th year of Advent |newspaper=The Hindu |date=23 November 2005|accessdate=10 January 2010|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> He won fame for his reputed mystical powers and ability to heal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/24/sri-sathya-sai-baba-dies|title=Sai Baba, spiritual guru to millions, dies at 85|author=Jason Burke|newspaper=the Guardian|date=2011-04-24}}</ref> In 1957 Sai Baba went on a North Indian temple tour.<ref name=\"Eade\"/>\n\n===Stroke, prediction of reincarnation and sole foreign tour===\n\nIn 1963, it was asserted that Sai Baba suffered a stroke and four severe heart attacks, which left him paralysed on one side. These events culminated in an event where he apparently healed himself in front of the thousands of people gathered in Prashanthi Nilayam who were then praying for his recovery.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/>\n\nOn recovering, Sai Baba announced that he would one day next be reborn as an incarnation named ''Prema Sai Baba'' in the neighbouring state of [[Karnataka]].<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/> He stated, \"I am Shiva-Sakthi, born in the [[gotra]] (lineage) of [[Bharadwaja]], according to a boon won by that sage from [[Shiva|Siva]] and [[Shakti|Sakthi]]. Siva was born in the gotra of that sage as Sai Baba of Shirdi; Shiva and Sakthi have incarnated as Myself in his gotra now; Sakthi alone will incarnate as the third Sai (Prema Sai Baba) in the same gotra in [[Mandya]] district of Karnataka State.\"<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/> He stated he would be born again eight years after his death at the age of 96, but died at the age of 84.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13180011 | work=BBC News | title=Satya Sai Baba, Indian guru, dies at 84 | date=24 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 June 1968, Sai Baba made his only overseas trip, to [[Kenya]] and [[Uganda]].\n\n===Later years===\n\nIn 1968, he established Dharmakshetra or the Sathyam Mandir in [[Mumbai]]. In 1973, he established the Shivam Mandir in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]]. On 19 January 1981, in [[Chennai]], he inaugurated the Sundaram Mandir.\n\nIn a [[1993 Murders in Prashanthi Nilayam|1993 incident]], four intruders armed with knives entered his bedroom, either as an assassination attempt or as part of a power struggle between his followers. Sai Baba was unharmed. During the scuffle and the police response, the intruders and two of Sai Baba's attendants were killed. The official investigation left questions unanswered.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/who-is-sri-sathya-sai-baba-101102|title=Who is Sri Sathya Sai Baba?|agency=Press Trust of India|date=24 April 2011|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/religion-obituaries/8471342/Sathya-Sai-Baba.html |title=Religion Obituaries; Satya Sai Baba |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=24 April 2011 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_sathya-sai-baba-escaped-murder-attempt_1535839 |title=Sathya Sai Baba escaped murder attempt|date=25 April 2011|last=Madhusoodan|first=M K |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1995, Sai Baba started a project to provide drinking water to 1.2&nbsp;million people in the drought-prone Rayalaseema region in the [[Anantapur district]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/water-projects-cm-all-praise-for-satya-sai-trust/article27563258.ece|title=Water projects: CM all praise for Satya Sai Trust|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2004-02-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-10-09|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> In April 1999 he inaugurated the Ananda Nilayam Mandir in [[Madurai]], Tamil Nadu.\n\nIn 2001 he established another free super-speciality hospital in [[Bangalore]] to benefit the poor.\n\n===Old age, illness and death===\n\nIn 2003, Sai Baba suffered a fractured hip when a student standing on an iron stool slipped and the boy and stool both fell on him. After that he gave [[darshana]] from a car or his porte chair.<ref name=\"ibnlive.in.com82-2\">{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sai-baba-turns-82-is-still-going-strong/52860-3.html?from=search-relatedstories|title=Sai Baba turns 82, is still going strong|last=Balakrishnan|first=Deepa|authorlink=|date=23 November 2007|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|accessdate=6 January 2010}}</ref> After 2004, Sai Baba used a wheelchair and began to make fewer public appearances.\n\n{{Wikinews|Renowned Indian guru \u015ar\u012b Satya Sai Baba dies aged 84}}\nOn 28 March 2011, Sai Baba was admitted to the [[Sri Sathya Sai Super Speciality Hospital]] at Prashantigram at Puttaparthi, following respiration-related problems.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Sai Baba in stable condition: Hospital| newspaper = [[Hindustan Times]]| date = 5 April 2011| url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/Sai-Baba-in-stable-condition-Hospital/Article1-681433.aspx| accessdate = 24 April 2011| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110509014742/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Sai-Baba-in-stable-condition-Hospital/Article1-681433.aspx| archivedate = 9 May 2011| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Baba's health condition 'stable' | newspaper = [[The Times of India]] | date = 6 April 2011 | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-06/hyderabad/29388337_1_vital-parameters-condition-crrt | accessdate = 24 April 2011}}</ref> After nearly a month of hospitalisation, during which his condition progressively deteriorated, Sai Baba died on Sunday, 24 April at 7:40 IST, aged 84.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Spiritual leader Sathya Sai Baba passes away | newspaper = [[The Times of India]] | date = 24 April 2011 | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-24/india/29468573_1_sai-baba-sathya-sai-central-trust-puttaparthi   | accessdate = 24 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nSai Baba had predicted that he would die at age 96 and would remain healthy until then.<ref>{{cite book|title=Redemptive Encounters: Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition|last=Babb|first=Lawrence A.|publisher=University of California Press|year=1991|isbn=978-0-520-07636-5|location=|page=[https://archive.org/details/redemptiveencoun0000babb/page/166 166]|quote=His present incarnation, he says, ... He will die at the age of ninety-six, but his body will stay young until then.|url=https://archive.org/details/redemptiveencoun0000babb/page/166}}</ref> After he died, some devotees suggested that he was referring to that many [[lunar calendar|lunar years]], as counted by Telugu-speaking Hindus, rather than [[tropical year|solar years]],<ref>Mohammed Shafeeq. However it was soon  clearly shown that the lunar reckoning does not work.  Post. Durban: 27 April 2011. pg. 4</ref> and using the [[hindu calendar|Indian way]] of [[Ageing#Cultural variations|accounting for age]], which counts the year to come as part of the person's life.<ref>Sri Philip M. Prasad, Malayalam Daily. Kerala, India: 25 April 2011. \"What Baba has foretold was indeed correct. According to the Roman calendar he has completed 85 years. But one can note that generally in all of Baba's discourses Baba had been referring to the star (lunar) basis in calculations. In Indian astrology there are 27 stars in a month starting with Aswathy and ending with Revathy. Accordingly a year of 12 months is composed of 324 days. Sai Baba was born on 23 November 1925. From that day till his death day 24 April 2011 there were a total of 33,899 days. If this is divided with 324, we get 95 years and 54 days. Accordingly, under the star basis of calculation he was in his 96th year having completed 54 days when he left his physical body.\"</ref> Other devotees have spoken of his anticipated [[resurrection]], [[reincarnation]] or [[wakefulness|awakening]].<ref>''The Hindustan Times'', New Delhi: 25 April 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Narayan |first1=Sreejith |title=Sai, Thy Kingdom Come | year = 2012| isbn = 978-1-62314-842-3 | url =http://www.saikingdom.com}}</ref>\n\n====Funeral and mourning====\n\nHis body lay in state for two days and was [[Burial|buried]] with full state honours on 27 April 2011.<ref name=\"news9\">News 9, 24 April 2011, 16:00 IST</ref> An estimated 500,000 people attended the burial, among them the Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]], [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] president [[Sonia Gandhi]], then Gujarat Chief Minister [[Narendra Modi]] (India's Present Prime Minister), Cricketer [[Sachin Tendulkar]] and [[Union Minister]]s [[S. M. Krishna]] and [[Ambika Soni]], as well as other political leaders and prominent figures.<ref>{{Cite news | title =Sathya Sai Baba gets a tearful farewell at his Puttaparthi home | newspaper=[[India Today]] | date = 27 April 2011 | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/sathya-sai-baba-last-rites-in-puttaparthi/1/136399.html|accessdate = 27 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2011/04/201142452416203714.html |title=Indian guru Sai Baba dies in hospital \u2013 Central & South Asia |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date= |accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_sathya-sai-baba-buried-in-puttaparthi_1536633 |title=Sathya Sai Baba buried in Puttaparthi |publisher=DNA |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/final-farewell-to-sathya-sai-baba-today/150310-3.html|title=Tearful farewell to Sathya Sai Baba |publisher=[[CNN-IBN]] |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nPolitical leaders who offered their condolences included the then Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]],<ref name=\"news9\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirchi9.com/news/2011/04/24/l-k-advani-reaction-on-sathya-sai-babas-death-tv9/|title=L.K.Advani Reaction on Sathya Sai Baba's Death :TV9 \u2013 Mirchi 9 \u2013 Telugu News &#124; Andhra News &#124; Hyderabad &#124; Andhra &#124; India &#124; Brain &#124; Studies &#124; University|publisher=Mirchi9.com|accessdate=24 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323040616/http://www.mirchi9.com/news/2011/04/24/l-k-advani-reaction-on-sathya-sai-babas-death-tv9/|archivedate=23 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://70mmonline.com/WatchMovie.aspx?movieid=9086&movieName=L.K.Advani%20Reaction%20on%20Sathya%20Sai%20Baba's%20Death|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018100215/http://70mmonline.com/WatchMovie.aspx?movieid=9086&movieName=L.K.Advani%20Reaction%20on%20Sathya%20Sai%20Baba's%20Death|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 October 2011|title=L.K.Advani Reaction on Sathya Sai Baba's Death, TV9 \u2013 L.K.Advani Reaction on Sathya Sai Baba's Death at|publisher=70mmonline.com|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref> Sri Lankan President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/news/2011/04/26/world-has-lost-great-spiritual-leader-sri-lankan-president-mahinda-rajapaksa|title=World has lost a great spiritual leader \u2013 Sri Lankan President Mahinda Rajapaksa|work=asiantribune.com}}</ref> and the [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://news.outlookindia.com/item.aspx?719929|title = Dalai Lama Mourns Sri Sathya Sai Baba's Death\n|publisher = outlookindia.com|date = 25 April 2011|accessdate = 29 May 2011}}</ref> Cricketer [[Sachin Tendulkar]], whose birthday was that day, cancelled his birthday celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketnext.in.com/news/sachin-mourns-sai-babas-death-on-his-bday/56827-13.html|title=Sachin mourns SaiBaba death on his b'day|date=24 April 2011|work=IBNLive}}</ref> ''[[The Hindu]]'' newspaper reported that \"Sri Sathya Sai Baba's propagation of spiritualism and preaching of Hindu philosophy never came in the way of his commitment to secular beliefs.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article1764337.ece?homepage=true | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=A secular spiritual leader | date=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Government of [[Karnataka]] declared 25 and 26 April as [[day of mourning|days of mourning]] and Andhra Pradesh declared 25, 26, and 27 April as days of mourning.<ref name=\"news9\"/>\n[[File:Sathya Sai Baba Samadhi at Puttaparthi, India.jpg|thumb|250px|Swamigal's Prashanthi Nilayam at Puttaparthi]]\n\n==Sathya Sai Organisation==\n{{Main|Sathya Sai Organisation}}\nThe Sathya Sai Organisation (or Sri Sathya Sai [[Selfless service|Seva]] Organization) was founded in the 1960s by Sathya Sai Baba.<ref name=\"srisaiorg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srisathyasai.org.in/Pages/Sai_Organisations/Sai_Organisations.htm|title=SSSCT- Sri Sathya Sai Seva Organisation|work=srisathyasai.org.in}}</ref> Initially called the \"Sri Sathya Sai Seva Samithi\",<ref name=\"saiindia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saibabaofindia.com/sai_baba_centers.htm|title=Sai Baba Of India-Sri Sathya Sai Baba Centers- Sai Baba organisation worldwide|work=saibabaofindia.com}}</ref> it was established \"to enable its members to undertake service activities as a means to spiritual advancement.\"<ref name=\"srisaiorg\"/>\n\nThe Sathya Sai Organisation reports that there are an estimated 1,200 Sathya Sai Baba Centres in 114 countries.<ref name=\"TheStarOnline84\">{{cite web |url=http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2009/12/3/north/5212802&sec=North |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521155709/http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=%2F2009%2F12%2F3%2Fnorth%2F5212802&sec=North |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 May 2011 |title=Sai Baba turns 84 |publisher=Thestar.com.my |date=3 December 2009 |accessdate=6 January 2010  }}</ref><ref name=\"SathyaSaiNumbers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sathyasai.org/organize/content.htm#SaiOrg|title=The Sai Organization: Numbers to Sai Centres and Names of Countries|publisher=Sathyasai.org|accessdate=6 January 2010}}</ref> However, the number of active Sai Baba followers is hard to determine.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\" /> Estimates vary from 6&nbsp;million<ref>[http://www.adherents.com/Na/Na_581.html#3510 Adherents] cites [[George Chryssides|Chryssides, George]]. ''Exploring New Religions''. London, UK: Cassells (1999) (10 million)<br />*Brown, Mick (2000-10-28). \"Divine Downfall\". Daily Telegraph. https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/main.jhtml?xml=/health/2000/10/28/tlbaba28.xml. Retrieved 2007-03-12<br />*Edwards, Linda (2001). A Brief Guide to Beliefs: Ideas, Theologies, Mysteries, and Movements. Westminster John Knox Press. {{ISBN|0-664-22259-5}}.</ref> up to nearly 100&nbsp;million.<ref>''[[The Economist]]'', [http://www.economist.com/node/18678803 \"Sai Baba\"], 14 May 2011, p. 110.</ref> In India itself, Sai Baba drew followers predominantly from the [[upper-middle-class]], the urban sections of society who have the \"most wealth, education and exposure to Western ideas.\"<ref name=\"UrbanHugh74\">{{cite journal|last=Urban|first=Hugh B.|author-link=Hugh Urban|year=2003|title=Avatar for Our Age: Sathya Sai Baba and the Cultural Contradictions of Late Capitalism|journal=[[Religion (journal)|Religion]]|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|volume=33|issue=1|page=74|doi=10.1016/S0048-721X(02)00080-5|issn=0048-721X|eissn=1096-1151}}</ref> In 2002, he claimed to have followers in 178 countries.<ref name=\"nyt1dec2002\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/01/world/a-friend-in-india-to-all-the-world.html?pagewanted=1|title=A Friend in India to All the World|last=Bradsher|first=Keith|date=1 December 2002|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Palmer97-98\">Palmer, Norris W. \"Baba's World\". In: {{cite book|last=Forsthoefel|first=Thomas A.|last2=Humes|first2=Cynthia Ann (eds.)|title=Gurus in America|place=Albany, New York|publisher=State University of New York Press|year=2005|pages=97\u201398|isbn=978-0-7914-6574-5}}</ref>\n\nSathya Sai Baba founded a large number of schools and colleges, hospitals, and other charitable institutions in India and abroad, the net financial capital of which is usually estimated at Rs. 400&nbsp;billion (US$9&nbsp;billion).<ref>\n{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/sathya-sai-baba-passes-away-leaves-behind-rs-40000-cr-worth-empire-with-no-clear-succession-plan/articleshow/8075953.cms|title=Sathya Sai Baba passes away, leaves behind Rs 40,000-cr worth empire with no clear succession plan\n|newspaper=[[The Economic Times|Economic Times]] | date=25 April 2011 |quote=Sai Baba leaves behind a wide network of charitable institutions, hospitals, schools, colleges, which some estimate to be worth about Rs 40,000 crore}}\n</ref><ref name=it>{{cite magazine|title=Up in the Heir: The secret world of Sathya Sai Baba's Rs 40,000 cr empire |author=Amarnath K. Menon |magazine=[[India Today]] |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/story/sathya-sai-baba-health-scare-assets-transition/1/135354.html |date=25 April 2011 |accessdate=9 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424073421/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/story/sathya-sai-baba-health-scare-assets-transition/1/135354.html |archivedate=24 April 2011 }}</ref><ref name=dh>{{cite news| title =Sai Baba's death leaves question mark on Rs 40,000 crore empire| author =Indo-Asian News Service| newspaper =    [[Deccan Herald]]| url =          http://www.deccanherald.com/content/156224/sai-babas-death-leaves-question.html| date = 24 April 2011\n|accessdate =9 June 2011| author-link =Indo-Asian News Service}}</ref> However, estimates as high as 1.4&nbsp;trillion rupees (about US$31.5bn) have also been made.<ref>{{cite news| title =Sathya Sai Baba trust worth Rs 1.4 lakh crore?|publisher =[[CNN-IBN]]| url =http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sathya-sai-baba-trust-worth-rs-14-lakh-crore/150273-3.html| date =26 April 2011| accessdate =9 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter his death, questions about the manner in which the finances of the organisation were going to be managed led to speculations of impropriety, with some reports suggesting that suitcases containing cash and/or gold had been removed from his personal lodgings.<ref name=\"dh\" /><ref>{{cite news| title =What's inside Sathya Sai's personal chamber?| publisher =    [[Zee News]]\n|url =http://zeenews.india.com/news710182.html| date =2 June 2011| accessdate =9 June 2011}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news| title =Trust hesitant on unlocking Sai Babas residence| author =Express News Service| publisher = [[CNN-IBN]]| url =http://ibnlive.in.com/news/trust-hesitant-on-unlocking-sai-babas-residence/155644-60-114.html\n|date =31 May 2011| accessdate =   9 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 2011, officials from the Sri Sathya Sai Central Trust opened his private residence in the presence of government, bank and tax department officials.<ref>Deccan Herald, Tuesday 17 June. 2011, \"Huge amount of gold, silver, cash found in Sai Baba's Chamber\" http://www.deccanherald.com/content/169535/huge-amount-gold-silver-cash.html.</ref> In the private residence, which had been sealed since his death, they inventoried 98&nbsp;kg of gold ornaments, approximate value Rs 21 [[crores]] (US$4.7m), 307&nbsp;kg of silver ornaments, approximate value Rs 16&nbsp;million (US$0.36m), and Rs 116&nbsp;million (US$2.6m) in cash. The cash was deposited into the Sai Trust's account at the State Bank of India with payment of government taxes (thus transferring them from religious gifts to Trust assets.) The gold and other items were inventoried, assessed, and placed in secure storage. In July, district authorities inventoried an additional Rs 7.7&nbsp;million (US$0.17m) in valuables in another 4 rooms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-03/india/29733031_1_satya-sai-baba-precious-metals-diamond-ring|title=Assets worth Rs 77L seized at Sai ashram|date=3 July 2011|newspaper=Times of India}}</ref> The total value of these items is believed to exceed 7.8&nbsp;million US dollars.<ref name=\"hindustan times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Treasure-island-Sai-Baba-s-gold-trove/Article1-710596.aspx|title=Treasure island: Sai Baba's gold trove|date=17 June 2011|publisher=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref> Also inventoried at Yajurmandir were thousands of pure silk sarees, dhotis, shirts, 500 pairs of shoes, dozens of bottles of perfume and hairspray, watches, a large number of silver and gold \"mangala sutrams\", and precious stones such as diamonds. There were also 750 saffron and white robes of the type Sai Baba wore.<ref name=\"500 pairs\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110618/jsp/nation/story_14130452.jsp|title=Open sesame! Baba & his chamber of secrets|author=G.S. Radhakrishna|date=17 June 2011|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph of India]]|location=Calcutta, India}} and [http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110618/images/18zzsaibababig.jpg this graphic]</ref> In July 2011, a similar opening of his Bangalore-area ashram tallied 6&nbsp;kg of gold coins and jewellery, 245&nbsp;kg of silver articles and Rs 8&nbsp;million in cash. These items and goods are believed to have been donated over the years by Sai Baba's devotees from all over the world as religious gifts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-21/bangalore/29798927_1_brindavan-revenue-officials-ashram|title=Three-day count at Baba's ashram yields treasure|date=21 July 2011|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/178661/perfumes-sarees-form-sai-babas.html,|title=Perfumes, sarees form Sai Baba's inventory|work=Deccan Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:Sri Sathya Sai Project 1999 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|A 1999 stamp devoted to the Sri Sathya Sai Water Supply Project]]\n[[File:Sathya Sai Baba 2013 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Sathya Sai Baba on a 2013 stamp of India]]\nOn 23 November 1999, the Department of Posts, [[Government of India]], released a postage stamp and a postal cover in recognition of the service rendered by Sai Baba in addressing the problem of providing safe drinking water to the rural masses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srisathyasai.org.in/Pages/Service_Projects/Anantapur.htm |title=SSSCT-Service Projects \u2013 Water Supply \u2013 Anantapur |publisher=Srisathyasai.org.in |date=23 November 1999 |accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> Another commemorative stamp was released on the occasion of what would have been his 88th birthday during November 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/postal-stamp-on-sathya-sai-baba-released/article5385073.ece|title=Postal stamp on Sathya Sai Baba released|date=24 November 2013|work=The Hindu|location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Postal-department-to-release-stamp-on-Sathya-Sai-Baba/articleshow/26168869.cms|title=Postal department to release stamp on Sathya Sai Baba \u2013 The Times of India|work=The Times Of India}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, an event was held in [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Chennai|Chennai Nehru Stadium]] organised by the Chennai Citizens' Conclave to thank Sai Baba for the 2&nbsp;billion water project which brought water from the [[River Krishna]] in Andhra Pradesh to Chennai city. Four chief ministers attended the function.<ref name=\"Chennai Visit\">[http://www.indianexpress.com/story/21444.html Felicitation for Water Project] Indian Express.</ref>\n\n==Ashrams and mandirs==\n\n===Prasanthi Nilayam===\n[[File:PrashantiNilayam1.jpg|left|thumb|Puttaparthi, A.P.]]\n{{Main|Prasanthi Nilayam}}\n[[File:Chaitanya Jyothi Museum, Prashanthi Nilayam, India.jpg|thumb|Chaitanya Jyoti Museum devoted to the life and teachings of Sathya Sai Baba]]\nPuttaparthi, where Sai Baba was born and lived, was originally a small, remote South Indian village in Andhra Pradesh. Now there is an extensive university complex, a speciality hospital, and two museums: the ''Sanathana Samskruti'' or Eternal Heritage Museum, sometimes called the Museum of All Religions, and the ''Chaitanya Jyoti'', devoted exclusively to the life and teachings of Sai Baba; the latter has won several international awards for its architectural design.<ref name=\"TheStar2005-04-02\">{{cite web |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=M. |title=Enlightening experience in India |publisher=The Star Online |date=2 April 2005 |url=http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=/2005/4/2/features/9982154&sec=features |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050412101614/http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=%2F2005%2F4%2F2%2Ffeatures%2F9982154&sec=features |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 April 2005 |accessdate=6 January 2010  }}</ref> There is also a planetarium, a railway station, a hill-view stadium, an administrative building, an airport, an indoor sports stadium and more.<ref>Places to see at Puttaparthi. [http://www.sathyasai.org/ashrams/prasanthi/outsideinterest.html Available online]</ref> High-ranking Indian politicians such as the former president [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]], former prime minister [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], Andhra Pradesh former chief minister [[Konijeti Rosaiah]] and [[Karnataka]] chief minister [[B. S. Yeddyurappa]] have been official guests at the ashram in Puttaparthi.<ref>''The Hindu'', \"A 5-point recipe for happiness\" 24 November 2006 [http://www.hindu.com/2006/11/24/stories/2006112405400400.htm Available online]</ref><ref>''The Hindu'', \"Warm welcome to PM at Puttaparthi\",12 February 2004 [http://www.hinduonnet.com/2004/02/12/stories/2004021203690600.htm Available online]</ref> It was reported that well over a million people attended Sai Baba's 80th birthday celebration, including 13,000 delegates from India and 180 other countries.<ref>''Deccan Herald'', \"Sathya Sai's birthday celebrations on\" by Terry Kennedy, 23 November 2005, [http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/nov232005/national1724520051122.asp Available online] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070501184330/http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/nov232005/national1724520051122.asp |date=1 May 2007 }}</ref>{{Citation needed |date=October 2013}}\n\n[[File:Hill in Prashanthi Nilayam with statues of Hanuman, Krishna, Shirdi Sai Baba, Shiva, Buddha, Christ, Zarathustra.jpg|thumb|Hill in Prashanthi Nilayam with statues of Hanuman, Krishna, Shirdi Sai Baba, Shiva, Buddha, Christ, Zarathustra.]]\n\nSai Baba resided much of the time in his main [[ashram]], ''Prashanthi Nilayam'' (Abode of Highest Peace), at Puttaparthi. In the summer he often left for his other ashram, ''Brindavan'', in Kadugodi, [[Whitefield, India|Whitefield]], a town on the outskirts of [[Bangalore]]. Occasionally he visited his Sai Shruti ashram in [[Kodaikanal]].<ref>The ashrams of Sathya Sai Baba. Referenced from the official Sathya Sai Organization website, [http://www.sathyasai.org/ashrams/content.html Available online]</ref>\n\n==Characteristics, beliefs and practices of devotees==\n{{Main|Sathya Sai Baba movement}}\nReliable sources often describe Sai Baba's following as a \"movement\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kent|first=Alexandra|date=1999|title=UNITY IN DIVERSITY: Portraying the Visions of the Sathya Sai Baba Movement of Malaysia|jstor=40800435|journal=Crossroads: An Interdisciplinary Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|volume=13\u20132|issue=2|pages=29\u201351}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sahoo|first=Ajaya Kumar|date=2013|title=Reconstructing Religious and Cultural Identity of Indians in the Diaspora: The Role of Sri Sathya Sai Baba Movement|jstor=23621024|journal=Sociological Bulletin|volume= 62| issue =  1 (January\u2013April 2013)|pages= 23\u201339|doi=10.1177/0038022920130102}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.americamagazine.org/content/all-things/death-god-man-sai-baba-dies-85|title=Death of a God-man? Sai Baba Dies at 85|last=Clooney|first=Francis X.|date=2011|work=America Magazine|access-date=}}</ref> A study by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) states \"A worldwide mass religious movement is growing around the Indian holy man and  miracle worker, Sathya Sai Baba.\" Later noting, \"The Sai Baba movement is likely to eventually become another worldwide religion.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP96-00792R000400280002-2.pdf|title=Cultural Trends Study \u2013 India's Sai Baba Movement|last=CIA|date=|website=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/cia-rdp96-00792r000400280002-2|access-date=}}</ref> Among scholars, we find it referred to often as either a \"[[New religious movement|New Religious Movement]]\" (NRM)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pereira|first=Shane N.|title=A New Religious Movement in Singapore: Syncretism and Variation in the Sathya Sai Baba Movement|jstor=23677933|journal= Asian Journal of Social Science|volume= 36| issue =  2|pages= 250\u2013270|year=2008|doi=10.1163/156853108X298699}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ekacha|first=Sanitsuda|date=2001|title=Keeping the Faith: Thai Buddhism at the Crossroads|journal=Nova Religio: The Journal of Alternative and Emergent Religions|volume= 9| issue = 2|pages=126\u2013128|doi=10.1525/nr.2005.9.2.126}}</ref> or as a  [[cult]],<ref name=das15/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Swallow|first1=D.A.|title=Living Saints and Their Devotees|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f1gkAQAAIAAJ&q=sathya+sai+baba+cult&dq=sathya+sai+baba+cult|date=1976|publisher=[PhD thesis summary published in ''Research in Social Anthropology, 1975\u20131980: A Register of Theses Accepted for Higher Degrees at British Universities, 1975\u20131980'', pp. 385\u2013386]}}</ref> it appears it is not immune to what Robbins and Zablocki, two social science researchers, call \"the divisive polarization, which, at least until recently, has plagued the academic study of religious movements.\" referencing a wide divide of two camps within academia, each preferring one term over the other (i.e. NRM or cult) for such groups';<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pJ9Nmc25xNAC&pg=PA515&dq=0802081886#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Misunderstanding Cults: Searching for Objectivity in a Controversial Field|last=Robbins & Zablocki|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=2001|isbn=978-0-8020-4373-3|location=|pages=3\u20135}}</ref> It's been noted by Eugene Gallagher, that in more modern times \"'New Religious movement', on the other hand, is a classification preferred by most academics, who see 'cult' as a pejorative term and intend to replace it with a more neutral label.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gallagher|first=Eugene|date=November 2007 \u2013 February 2008|title=\"Cults\" and \"New Religious Movements\"|jstor=10.1086/524210|journal=History of Religions, University of Chicago Press|volume= 47| issue =  2/3|pages=205\u2013220|doi=10.1086/524210}}</ref> It is regarded by most scholars to be of Hindu persuasion.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Babb|first1=L. A.|editor1-last=Hawley|editor1-first=J.S.|title=Saints and Virtues|date=1987|publisher=University of California Press|location=London (UK)|isbn=978-0-520-06163-7|pages=168\u2013186|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RGv2wOUl0pMC&dq|chapter=Sathya Sai Baba's Saintly Play}}</ref><ref>Alexandra Kent Divinity and diversity: a Hindu revitalization movement in Malaysia, NIAS, 2005</ref><ref>Handoo, Jawaharlal in ''Asian Folklore Studies'', Vol. 48, No. 2 (1989), pp. 326\u201332 reviewing Lawrence A. Babb's book ''Redemptive Encounters. Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition'' [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1177938 page 1]</ref><ref>Nagel, Alexandra (note: Nagel is a critical former follower) \"De Sai Paradox: Tegenstrijdigheden van en rondom Sathya Sai Baba\"/\"The Sai Paradox contradictions of and surrounding Sathya Sai Baba\" from the magazine \"Religieuze Bewegingen in Nederland, 'Sekten' \"/\"Religious movements in the Netherlands, 'Cults/Sects' \", 1994, nr. 29. published by the [[Free University of Amsterdam]] press, (1994) {{ISBN|90-5383-341-2}}<br> Dutch original: \"Ofschoon Sai Baba gezegd heeft mensen van allerlei religieuze gezindten te helpen terug te gaan naar oude waarden en normen, en ofschoon zijn logo de symbolen van de andere grote godsdiensten bevat, is de sfeer rondom Sai Baba duidelijk hindoe\u00efstisch gekleurd. Alle moslim-elementen bijv. waarvan verondersteld zou kunnen worden dat hij die zou hebben meegenomen uit zijn leven als Sai Baba van Shirdi, heeft hij laten vallen. Het enig echt herkenbare wat hij van Shirdi Baba nog heeft, is het veelvuldig gebruik van as, \u2013 wat hij dan niet uit een dhuni haalt zoals Shirdi Baba deed, maar materialiseert (of tevoorschijn goochelt)\"</ref>\n\nSai Baba claimed to be the reincarnation of Sai Baba of Shirdi, and his followers considered him to be the [[Avatar]] of [[Shiva]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WA12nHRtmAwC&pg=PA307 |author=Chryssides, George D. |title=Historical dictionary of new religious movements |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2012|isbn=9780810861947 }}</ref> Sai Baba of Shirdi was known to combine Islamic and Hindu teachings; still Charles S. J. White, of [[The American University]] at Washington D.C., noted of Sathya Sai Baba in 1972, that \"there is no discernible Muslim influence.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=White|first1=Charles S. J.|title=The Sai Baba Movement: Approaches to the Study of India Saints|journal=The Journal of Asian Studies|date=1972|volume=31|issue=4|pages=863\u2013878|doi=10.2307/2052105|jstor=2052105}}</ref> Stephanie Tallings, in The Harvard international Review, noted Sai Baba's following is drawn from people of all religions, ethnicities, and social classes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tallings|first=Stephanies|date=Summer 2000|title=Avatar of Stability: Sai Baba's Teachings|url=https://www.jstor.org/publisher/hir|journal=Harvard International Review|volume= 22| issue =  2|pages=14\u201315|via=}}</ref> Lawrence A. Babb, of the Amherst College in Massachusetts, labelled Sai Baba movement as a cult in the 1980s, calling it \"deeply and authentically Hindu...\" and noted, \"The most striking feature of this cult, however, is the extremely strong emphasis given to the miraculous.\"<ref name=\"babb83\" /> However, a scholarly review claims Babb misapplies the word \u201ccult\u201d, responding, \"the so-called 'cult' of Satya Sai Baba seems to possess all such characteristics which are, according to the author, central to a religious movement.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Handoo|first=Jawaharlal|date=1989|title=Reviewed Work: Redemptive Encounters. Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition by Lawrence A. Babb|url=http://asianethnology.org/downloads/ae/pdf/a759.pdf|journal=Asian Folklore Studies|volume= 48| issue =  2|page=327|via=}}</ref> Deborah A. Swallow, of the University of Cambridge, referred to it as a cult and said that the \"ritual and theology, then, unlike Sai Baba [of Shirdi]'s, is distinctly Hindu in form and content.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Swallow|first1=D. A.|title=Ashes and Powers: Myth, Rite and Miracle in an Indian God-Man's Cult|journal=Modern Asian Studies|date=2008|volume=16|issue=1|pages=123\u2013158|doi=10.1017/S0026749X0000072X|jstor=312277}}</ref> But John D. Kelly, a professor of anthropology at the University of Chicago, wrote about Hindu missions in Fiji that the Sathya Sai Organization (which is part of the movement) rejected the label Hindu. According to Kelly, they see their founder as the \"living synthesis of the world's religious traditions\" and prefer to be classified as an [[interfaith]] movement. But he observed that Sai Baba mission is a Hindu mission as active as Christian or Muslim missions.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kelly|first1=J.D.|editor1-last=van der Veer|editor1-first=P.|title=Nation and Migration: The Politics of Space in the South Asian Diaspora|date=1995|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Philadelphia (US)|isbn=978-0-8122-1537-3|pages=43\u201372|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bvTHlLRZL8UC&dq|chapter=Bhakti and Postcolonial Politics: Hindu Missions to Fiji}}</ref> In a 2001 scholarly book Tulasi Srinivas, notes, \"The Sathya Sai global civil religious movement incorporates Hindu and Muslim practices, Buddhist, Christian, and Zoroastrian influences, and \"New Age\"-style rituals and beliefs.\u2019 And in the appendix of the book (p. 349) lists 10 scholarly authors/researchers in both Europe and America who all refer to it as a New Religious Movement (NRM).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Winged Faith: Rethinking Globalization and Religious Pluralism through the Sathya Sai Movement|last=Srinivas|first=Tulasi|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=June 2010|isbn=9780231149334|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSai Baba was known for his quote \"Love All, Serve All. Help Ever, Hurt Never.\"<ref name=\"Leslie-Chaden2004\">{{cite book|author=Charlene Leslie-Chaden|title=A compendium of the teachings of Sri Sathya Sai Baba|url=http://puttaparthi.info/shopping/shp/bookdetail.asp?itemid=B1001|accessdate=24 April 2011|year=2004|publisher=Sai Towers Publishing|page=526|isbn=978-81-7899-042-2}} {{self-published source|date=April 2011}}</ref>{{Self-published inline|date=April 2011}}<ref name=\"Architectural digest\">{{cite book|title=Architectural digest|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YcxUAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=24 April 2011|date=1 May 1994|publisher=Conde Nast Publications}}</ref> Internationally, his devotees gather daily, or weekly on Sundays or Thursdays or both, for [[bhajans|devotional songs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sathyasai.ca/ |title=Sri Sathya Sai Baba Organization in Canada \u2013 Home Page |publisher=Sathyasai.ca |date=1 May 2006 |accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> prayer,<ref name=\"saius\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110727120609/http://us.sathyasai.org/resources/06oct15CenterGuidelines12.pdf Guidelines for AMERICAN SATHYA SAI BABA CENTERS]. The Sathya Sai Baba Central Council of the United States of America (2006)</ref> spiritual meditation, service to the community (Seva),<ref name=\"saito\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sathyasaitoronto.org/ |title=The Sri Sathya Sai Baba Centre of Toronto \u2013 York |publisher=Sathyasaitoronto.org |date= |accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> and to participate in \"Education in Human Values\" (SSEHV)<ref name=\"saius\"/> known as \"''Bal Vikas''\" (Blossoming of the Child).\n\nFollowers believed in seeking the spiritual benefit of Sai Baba's ''[[darsana|darshan]]'', scheduled for morning and afternoon each day. Sai Baba would interact with people, accept letters, materialise and distribute [[vibhuti]] (sacred ash) or call groups or individuals for interviews. Devotees considered it a great privilege to have an interview and sometimes a single person, group or family was invited for a private interview for answers to spiritual questions and general guidance.<ref name=\"kent\"/>\n\nThe ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'' in 2001 reported that Sai Baba told his adherents not to browse the internet.<ref name=\"VS\">{{Cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/staff-blogs/sai-baba-holy-man-sex-abuser-both|title=Sai Baba: Holy man? Sex abuser? Both?|date=2011-04-26|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n=== Criticism ===\nAccusations<!-- Please do not change this wording, this has been agreed on the talk page. If you don't agree on it read the discussion there. --> against Sai Baba by his critics over the years have included sleight of hand, sexual abuse, money laundering, fraud in the performance of service projects, and murder.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/><ref name=Palmer116/>\n\nIn 1972 [[Abraham Kovoor]] made the first public criticism of Sai Baba<ref name=\"srisathyasaibabaandthepress\">Ruhela S.P., ''Sri Sathya Sai Baba and the Press'', pp. 1\u20135, 1997 {{ISBN|81-7533-041-4}}</ref> when he looked into a claim publicly narrated by one devotee<ref name=\"srisathyasaibabaandthepress\" /> that Sai Baba had created a new model of a [[Seiko]] watch, and found the claim to be untrue.<ref name=\"sathyasaibabasgrace\">Ruhela S.P., ''How to Receive Sri Sathya Sai Baba's Grace'', pp. 277, 2006 {{ISBN|81-7182-089-1}}</ref><ref name=OutlookSingh>{{cite web|title=The Spell Breaker|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?262445|publisher=Outlook|accessdate=16 October 2013|author=Rahul Singh|date=2 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1976, [[Hosur Narasimhaiah|Hossur Narasimhaiah]], a physicist, rationalist and then vice-chancellor of [[Bangalore University]], founded and chaired a committee \"to rationally and scientifically investigate miracles and other verifiable superstitions\". Narasimhaiah wrote Sai Baba three widely publicised letters challenging him to perform his miracles under controlled conditions. The letters were ignored.<ref name=\"haraldsson204\">Haraldson, ''op. cit'', pp&nbsp;204\u2013205</ref> Sai Baba said that he ignored Narasimhaiah's challenge because he felt that a scientific approach to spiritual issues was improper, adding that \"Science must confine its inquiry only to things belonging to the human senses, while spiritualism transcends the senses. If you want to understand the nature of spiritual power you can do so only through the path of spirituality and not science. What science has been able to unravel is merely a fraction of the cosmic phenomena&nbsp;...\"<ref name=\"blitz\">Interview given by Sai Baba to [[R. K. Karanjia]] of ''Blitz'' news magazine in September 1976 [http://www.saibaba.ws/articles/interviewwithjournalistsept1976.htm Available online]</ref> Narasimhaiah's committee was dissolved in August 1977. Narasimhaiah held the fact that Sai Baba ignored his letters to be an indication that his miracles were fraudulent.<ref>Haraldsson, pp 209</ref> As a result of this episode, a public debate raged for several months in Indian newspapers.<ref>Haraldsson, ''op. cit.'', pp. 206</ref>\n\nIndian rationalist [[Basava Premanand]], who began campaigning against Sai Baba in 1976, unsuccessfully attempted to sue him in 1986 for violations of the [[Gold Control Act]], citing Sai Baba's purported materialisations of gold objects. When the case was dismissed, Premanand unsuccessfully appealed on the grounds that claimed spiritual power is not a defence recognised in law.<ref name=bbca1>{{cite news|author=Tanya Datta|title=Sai Baba: Goan or con man?|date=17 June 2004|work=[[BBC News]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/this_world/3813469.stm | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nA 1995 TV documentary ''Guru Busters'', produced by filmmaker [[Robert Eagle (writer and director)|Robert Eagle]] for the UK's [[Channel 4]], accused Sai Baba of faking his materialisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eagletv.co.uk/home/guru.htm |title=Eagle & Eagle |publisher=Eagletv.co.uk |date= |accessdate=7 January 2010}} [http://www.eagletv.co.uk/home/videos/Saimagic.mov Clip]</ref> The clip from the film was mentioned in the ''[[Deccan Chronicle]]'', on 23 November 1992, in a front-page headline \"DD Tape Unveils Baba Magic\".<ref>Haraldsson, ''op. cit.'', pp.&nbsp;295\u2013301</ref>\n\nIn 1998, British journalist Mick Brown stated in his book ''The Spiritual Tourist'' that in his opinion claims of Sai Baba resurrecting American devotee Walter Cowan in 1971 were probably untrue.<ref name=\"spiritualtourist\">Mick Brown, ''The Spiritual Tourist'', 1998, Bloomsbury Publishing, {{ISBN|1-58234-034-X}} \"In the House of God\", pp.&nbsp;73\u201374</ref> His opinion was based on letters from the attending doctors presented in the magazine ''[[Indian Skeptic]]'', published by Basava Premanand.<ref name=\"spiritualtourist\"/><ref>Hislop, John S. ''My Baba and I'' 1985 published by Birth Day Publishing Company, San Diego, California {{ISBN|0-9600958-8-8}}, \"The Resurrection of Walter Cowan\", pages&nbsp;28\u201331</ref> Brown also related, in the same book, his experiences with manifestations of ''vibuthi'' from Sai Baba's pictures in houses in London, which he felt were not fraudulent or the result of trickery.<ref name=\"touristmiracle\">Brown Mick, ''The Spiritual Tourist'', \"The Miracle in North London\", pp.&nbsp;29\u201330, 1998 {{ISBN|158234034X}}</ref> Brown wrote with regards to Sai Baba's claims of omniscience, that \"sceptics have produced documentation clearly showing discrepancies between Baba's reading of historical events and biblical prophecies, and the established accounts.\"<ref name=\"spiritualtourist\"/>\n\n===Allegations of  abuse===\nIn January 2002, a documentary produced by Denmark's national television and radio broadcast company, [[Danish radio|Danmarks Radio]] (DR), called ''Seduced By Sai Baba'', analysed videos of public manifestations of Sai Baba and suggested that they could be explained as [[sleight of hand]].<ref name=\"seduced\">{{cite video|people=\u00d8yvind Kyr\u00f8, Steen Jensen |title=Seduced by Sai Baba |medium=Documentary |publisher=[[DR (broadcaster)|DR]] |date=2002 |url=http://dr.dk/Salg/DRsales/Programmes/Documentary/Society_and_Social/20070629133445_3_1_3_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204010039/http://www.dr.dk/Salg/DRsales/Programmes/Documentary/Society_and_Social/20070629133445_3_1_3_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1.htm |archivedate=4 February 2010 }}</ref> The documentary also presented interviews with Alaya Rahm, former devotee of Sathya Sai Baba, where he alleged abuse by Sathya Sai Baba.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/> As a result, in 2002 the parliament of the United Kingdom discussed the possible danger to male children of British families intending to visit the ashram of Sathya Sai Baba in case of individual audiences with the guru.<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2001-02/886] UK Parliament official web site</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[BBC]] produced a documentary titled ''The Secret Swami'' as part of its series \"The World Uncovered\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/this_world/3791921.stm |title=Programmes &#124; This World &#124; Secret Swami |work=BBC News |date=11 June 2004 |accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> One central theme of the BBC documentary was again Alaya Rahm's sexual abuse allegations against Sathya Sai Baba.<ref name=bbcd>{{cite video|people=Eamon Hardy, Tanya Datta|title=Secret Swami|medium=Documentary|publisher=BBC News|date=2004 |time= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/this_world/3791921.stm | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> This documentary interviewed him together with Mark Roche, who had spent 25 years of his life since 1969 in the movement and alleged abuse by Sai Baba.<ref name=bbcd/> The show also featured allegations from Sai Baba critic Basava Premanand. Premanand stated in the documentary that, in his opinion, Sai Baba faked his materialisations.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n===Responses===\nSathya Sai Baba and his followers reject any allegations of misconduct.<ref name=funeral/> Devotee [[Bill Aitken (traveller)|Bill Aitken]] was quoted by ''[[The Week]]'' as saying that Sathya Sai Baba's reputation had not been harmed by the negative stories published about him. He said that the more detractors railed against Sathya Sai Baba, the more new devotees went to see him.<ref>Aitken, Bill (27 November 2005),{{cite web|url=http://www.the-week.com/25nov27/currentevents_article10.htm |title=Miracle of Welfare |accessdate=9 September 2006 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909111636/http://www.the-week.com/25nov27/currentevents_article10.htm |archivedate=9 September 2006  }}</ref>\n\nIn the article ''Divine Downfall'', published in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', Anil Kumar, the ex-principal of the Sathya Sai Educational Institute, said that he believed that the controversy was part of Sathya Sai Baba's divine plan and that all great religious teachers had to face criticism during their lives. Anil Kumar also said that allegations had been levelled at Sathya Sai Baba since childhood, but with every criticism he had become more and more triumphant.<ref name=\"divine\">Brown, Mick (28 October 2000). \"Divine Downfall\". Daily Telegraph.</ref>\n\nIn the book ''Redemptive Encounters: Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition'', Lawrence A. Babb wrote of Sathya Sai Baba, \"Whoever he is, he is certainly more than the mere parlour magician many of his critics claim that he is.\"<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/>\n\nSathya Sai Baba publicly responded to the allegations on 25 December 2000:\n{{quote|Some people out of their mean-mindedness are trying to tarnish the image of Sai Baba. I am not after name and fame. So, I do not lose anything by their false allegations. My glory will go on increasing day by day. It will never diminish even a bit if they were to publicise their false allegations in the whole world in bold letters. Some devotees seem to be perturbed over these false statements. They are not true devotees at all. Having known the mighty power of Sai, why should they be afraid of the 'cawing of crows'? One should not get carried away by all that is written on walls, said in political meetings or the vulgar tales carried by the print media.<ref>Sathya Sai Speaks Vol.33, pg.389</ref>}}\n\n''[[The Times of India]]'' on 26 December 2000 quoted Sathya Sai Baba as saying: {{quote|[[Jesus Christ]] underwent many hardships, and was put to the cross because of jealousy. Many around him could not bear the good work he did and the large number of followers he gathered. One of his disciples, [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]], betrayed him. In those days there was one Judas, but today there are thousands. Just as that Judas was tempted to betray Jesus, the Judases of today, too, are bought out to lie. Jealousy was the motive behind the allegations levelled at him.<ref>Rao, Manu (26 December 2000), Sai Baba lashes out at detractors http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bangalore/sai-baba-lashes-out-at-detractors/articleshow/534425761.cms</ref>}}\n\nIn an official letter made public in December 2001, [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]] (then [[Prime Minister of India]] and a devotee of Sai Baba),<ref name=Palmer97-98 /> [[P. N. Bhagwati|P.N. Bhagwati]] (Former Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of India), [[Ranganath Misra]] (Chair Person, National Human Rights Commissioner of India and Former Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of India), [[Najma Heptulla]] (President of the Inter-Parliamentary Union; UNDP Distinguished Human Development Ambassador) and [[Shivraj V. Patil|Shivraj Patil]] (Member of Parliament, India; Formerly of the Lok Sabha & Union Minister) all signed the following statement:\n\n{{quote|We are deeply pained and anguished by the wild, reckless and concocted allegations made by certain vested interests and people against Bhagwan Sri Sathya Sai Baba. We would normally expect that responsible media would ascertain the true facts before printing such a calumny \u2013 especially when the person is revered globally as an embodiment of love and selfless service to humanity.<ref name=\"letterpmindia\">Letter from A.B. Vajpayee (the then Prime Minister of India), http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fline/fl2810/stories/20110520281002600.htm</ref><ref>Official Letter, http://www.saibaba.ws/images/letter_pm_india.gif</ref> }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Samuel H. Sandweiss|title=Sai Baba the Holy Man and the Psychiatrist|isbn=978-0-960-09581-0|year=1975|page=[https://archive.org/details/saibabaholymanps0000sand/page/240 240]|url=https://archive.org/details/saibabaholymanps0000sand/page/240}}\n* {{cite book|author=John S. Hislop|title=My Baba and I|isbn=978-0-960-09588-9|year=1985|url=https://archive.org/details/mybabai00hisl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Phyllis Krystal|title=Sai Baba: The Ultimate Experience|isbn=978-0-877-28794-0|year=1994|page=260}}\n* {{cite book|author=Don Mario Mazzoleni|title=A Catholic Priest Meets Sai Baba|isbn=978-0-962-98351-1|year=1994|page=[https://archive.org/details/catholicpriestme00mazz/page/285 285]|url=https://archive.org/details/catholicpriestme00mazz/page/285}}\n* {{cite book|author=Erlendur Haraldsson|title=Modern Miracles: An Investigative Report on These Psychic Phenomena Associated With Sathya Sai Baba|isbn=978-0-803-89384-9|year=1997|page=[https://archive.org/details/modernmiracles00erle/page/315 315]|url=https://archive.org/details/modernmiracles00erle/page/315}}\n* {{cite book|author=Vladimir Antonov|title=Sathya Sai Baba \u2013 The Christ of Our Days|isbn=978-1-438-25276-6|year=2008|page=38}}\n* {{cite book|author=Tommy S. W. Wong|title=How Sai Baba Attracts Without Direct Contact|isbn=978-1-448-60416-6|year=2009|page=108}}\n* {{cite book|author=Tulasi Srinivas|title=Winged Faith: Rethinking Globalization and Religious Pluralism Through the Sathya Sai Movement|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-14933-4|year=2010|page=430}}\n* {{cite book|author=David Smith|title=\"Hinduism\" Religions in the Modern World: Traditions and Transformations|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-85880-9|year=2016}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wikinews|Sai Baba upsets Telangana activists}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.sathyasai.org/ International Sai Organization]\n* {{Curlie|Society/Religion_and_Spirituality/Hinduism/Gurus_and_Saints/Sathya_Sai_Baba/}} \n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Sathya Sai Baba}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n80-7665}}\n\n{{Sathya Sai Baba}}\n{{Hindu reform movements}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT KEEP REMOVING THIS PAGE FROM THE \"HINDU SAINTS\" CATEGORY WITHOUT FIRST EXPLAINING YOUR REASONS ON THE TALK-PAGE.-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baba, Sathya Sai}}\n[[Category:Sathya Sai Baba| ]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian spiritual teachers]]\n[[Category:People from Anantapur district]]\n[[Category:People from Rayalaseema]]\n[[Category:People considered avatars by their followers]]\n[[Category:Puttaparthi]]\n[[Category:Psychokineticists]]\n[[Category:Religious pluralism]]\n[[Category:Self-declared messiahs]]\n[[Category:State funerals in India]]\n[[Category:Tantra]]\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Tantric practices]]\n[[Category:Telugu people]]\n[[Category:Burials in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian guru}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox Hindu leader\n|name              = Sathya Sai Baba\n|image             = Bhagawan_Sri_Sathya_Sai_Baba.jpg\n|alt               =\n|caption           =\n| religion = [[Hinduism]]\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date|1926|11|23|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Puttaparthi]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n|death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2011|4|24|1926|11|23}}\n|death_place       = Puttaparthi, [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]]\n|birth_name        = Sathyanarayana Raju\n|founder           = [[Sathya Sai Organization]] \n|guru              = <!-- The teacher (if any) -->\n|philosophy        = Love all. Serve all.\nHelp Ever. Hurt Never.\n|nationality       = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n|signature         =\n}}\n{{Hindu philosophy}} \n'''Sathya Sai Baba''' (born '''Sathyanarayana Raju'''; 23 November 1926{{spaced ndash}}24 April 2011<ref name=\"BBC obit\">{{cite news |publisher=BBC| title=Obituary: Indian guru Sai Baba |date= 24 April 2011|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13153536 |quote=Satya Sai Baba was born Sathyanarayana Raju on 23 November 1926}}</ref>) was an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Tantra|guru]] and philanthropist.<ref name=\"babb83\">{{cite journal|last1=Babb|first1=Lawrence A.|title=Sathya Sai Baba's Magic|journal=Anthropological Quarterly|date=1983|volume=56|issue=3|pages=116\u2013124|doi=10.2307/3317305|jstor=3317305}}</ref><ref name=\"das15\">{{cite journal|last1=Das|first1=M. K.|title=Televising religion: A study of Sathya Sai Baba's funeral broadcast in Gangtok, India|journal=Anthropological Notebooks|date=2015|volume=21|issue=3|pages=83\u2013104|url=http://www.drustvo-antropologov.si/AN/PDF/2015_3/Anthropological_Notebooks_XXI_3_Kumar%20Das.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"RichardWeiss\">{{cite journal|last1=Weiss|first1=Richard|date=December 2005|title=THE GLOBAL GURU: SAI BABA AND THE MIRACLE OF THE MODERN|url=http://www.nzasia.org.nz/downloads/NZJAS-Dec05/7_2_2.pdf|journal=New Zealand Journal of Asian Studies|volume=7|issue=2|pages=5\u201319}}</ref> At the age of fourteen he claimed that he was the [[reincarnation]] of [[Sai Baba of Shirdi|Shirdi Sai Baba]],<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\" /><ref name=\"kent\" /> and encouraged his followers to believe the same.<ref name=\"Singleton, Mark| Goldberg, Ellen\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GSpnAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT208&dq=sai+baba+god+incarnate+academic+studies#v=onepage&q=sai%20baba%20god%20incarnate%20academic%20studies&f=false|title=Gurus of Modern Yoga|isbn=9780199374953|last1=Singleton|first1=Mark|last2=Goldberg|first2=Ellen|date=27 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"BabbLawrence\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Redemptive_Encounters.html?id=B8bMjUt6AqIC|title=Redemptive Encounters: Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition|last=Babb|first=Lawrence A.|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=1991|isbn=978-0-520-07636-5|location=|page=164}}</ref>\n\nSathya Sai Baba's purported [[Materialization (parapsychology)|materialisations]] of ''[[Vibhuti#Sacred ash|vibhuti]]'' (holy ash) and other small objects such as rings, necklaces, and watches, were a source of controversy.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/this_world/3813469.stm|title=Sai Baba: God-man or con man?|last=Datta|first=Tanya|date=17 June 2004|work=BBC News}}</ref> Some have analyzed them as being mere [[sleight of hand|sleights of hand]]; while his followers have considered them as signs of his divinity.<ref name=\"quack\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=55wFpydSZ8oC&pg=PA120|title=Disenchanting India: Organized Rationalism and Criticism of Religion in India|author=Johannes Quack|date=22 November 2011|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-981260-8|location=|pages=120}}</ref><ref name=\"CNNSingh\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/04/24/india.spiritual.guru.death/|title=Indian spiritual guru dies at 85|author=Harmeet Shah Singh|date=24 April 2011|newspaper=CNN|accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref> Reports of [[faith healing]]s have been attributed to Sathya Sai Baba by his followers.<ref name=\"Palmer116\">Palmer, Norris W. \"Baba's World\". In: {{cite book|title=Gurus in America|last=Forsthoefel|first=Thomas A.|last2=Humes|first2=Cynthia Ann (eds.)|publisher=State University of New York Press|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7914-6574-5|place=Albany, NY|author-link=|author2-link=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Modern Miracles: Sathya Sai Baba The Story of a Modern Day Prophet|last=Haraldsson Ph.D|first=Erlendur|publisher=Rider|year=1987|isbn=978-1-908733-25-2|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sathya Sai Organisation]], founded by Sathya Sai Baba \"to enable its members to undertake service activities as a means to spiritual advancement\",<ref name=\"srisaiorg\"/> has over 1,200 Sathya Sai Centres (branches) in 126 countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Branches|url=http://www.sathyasai.org/organize/content.htm|publisher=Official website \u2013 International Sai Organisation|accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref> Through this organisation, Sathya Sai Baba established a network of free hospitals, clinics, drinking water projects, auditoriums, [[ashram]]s and schools.<ref name=funeral>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13204914|title=Thousands flock to funeral of India guru Satya Sai Baba|work=BBC News|date=27 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=deccanheraldlegacy>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/156315/sai-babas-legacy.html|title=Sai Baba's legacy|work=Deccan Herald|date=2011-04-24}}</ref><ref name=\"toigovernments\">{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-25/india/29470992_1_sathya-sai-baba-whitefield-ashram-god | work=The Times Of India | title='Sai Baba did everything govt could not' \u2013 The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n===Early life===\n\nAlmost everything known about Sathya Sai Baba's early life stems from the [[hagiography]] that grew around him, narratives that hold special meaning to his devotees and are considered by them to be evidence of his divine nature.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/><ref name=\"UrbanHugh74\" /><ref name=\"Palmer99\">{{cite book|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/4991|title=Gurus in America|last=Palmer|first=Norris W.|publisher=[[State University of New York Press]]|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7914-6574-5|editor-last=A. Forsthoefel|editor-first=Thomas|place=Albany, NY|page=99|chapter=Baba\u2019s World: A Global Guru and His Movement|editor-last2=Ann Humes|editor-first2=Cynthia|chapter-url=https://muse.jhu.edu/chapter/116246}}</ref> According to these sources, Sathya Narayana Raju was born to Meesaraganda Easwaramma and Peddavenkama Raju Ratnakaram in the village of [[Puttaparthi]], to a [[Bhatraju]] family,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/south/story/a-phenomenon-called-sathya-sai-baba-132676-2011-04-25|title=A phenomenon called Sathya Sai Baba|last=Rao|first=A. Srinivasa|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=6fHFLQDOEuYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=bhat%20raju&f=false|title=Winged Faith: Rethinking Globalization and Religious Pluralism through the Sathya Sai Movement|last=Srinivas|first=Tulasi|date=2010-06-10|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-52052-2|location=|pages=54|language=en}}</ref> an [[Other Backward Class|OBC]] community of religious musicians and balladeers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/35458340.pdf|title=Sathya Sai Baba as Avatar: \"His Story\" and the History of an Idea|last=Spurr|first=Michael James|date=|website=University of Canterbury|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GSpnAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT368&dq=Bhatraju#v=onepage&q=Bhat%20raju&f=false|title=Gurus of Modern Yoga|last=Singleton|first=Mark|last2=Goldberg|first2=Ellen|date=2013-11-27|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-937495-3|language=en}}</ref> in what was the [[Madras Presidency]] of [[British Raj|British India]].<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/><ref>Haraldsson, Erlendur, Miracles are my visiting cards \u2013 An investigative inquiry on Sathya Sai Baba, (1997 revised and updated edition published by Sai Towers, Prasanthi Nilayam, India), p. 55, {{ISBN|81-86822-32-1}}</ref><ref name=\"Eade\">{{Cite book|date=2002-01-01|editor-last=Eade|editor-first=John|editor2-last=Mele|editor2-first=Christopher|title=Understanding the City|publisher=Wiley|language=en|doi=10.1002/9780470693582|isbn=9780470693582}}</ref> His birth was alleged by his mother Easwaramma to be of a [[Miraculous births|miraculous conception]].<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/><ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/>\n\nSathya Sai Baba's siblings included elder brother Ratnakaram Seshama Raju (1911\u20131985), sisters Venkamma (1918\u20131993) and Parvathamma (1920\u20131998), and younger brother Janakiramaiah (1931\u20132003).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-22/india/29463028_1_sathya-sai-baba-satyajit-trust-affairsnephew|title=Vaastu dosham at hospital he built, say Sai kin|last=|first=|date=25 April 2011|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs a child, he was described as \"unusually intelligent\" and charitable, though not necessarily academically inclined, as his interests were of a more spiritual nature.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/><ref name=Palmer99 /> He was uncommonly talented in devotional music, dance and drama.<ref name=Palmer99 /><ref name=\"kent\">{{cite book | last = Kent | first = Alexandra | authorlink = |title =Divinity and Diversity: A Hindu Revitalization Movement in Malaysia |publisher = Nordic Institute of Asian Studies | year = 2005  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=26sVhUo_aM4C&pg=PA37 |pages = 37\u201339| isbn = 978-87-91114-40-3}}</ref> From a young age, he has been alleged to have been capable of materialising objects such as food and sweets out of thin air.<ref name=\"AlexandraKent\">{{Cite journal|last=Kent|first=Alexandra|date=2000-01-01|title=Creating Divine Unity: Chinese Recruitment in the Sathya Sai Baba Movement of Malaysia|journal=Journal of Contemporary Religion|volume=15|issue=1|pages=5\u201327|doi=10.1080/135379000112116|issn=1353-7903}}</ref>\n\n===Proclamation===\n\n[[File:Baba-1940's.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Sai Baba at the age of 14, soon after proclaiming he was the reincarnation of Shirdi Sai Baba]]\nOn 8 March 1940, while living with his elder brother Seshama Raju in [[Uravakonda]], a small town near Puttaparthi, 14 year old Sathya was apparently stung by a scorpion.<ref name=\"AlexandraKent\"/> He lost consciousness for several hours<ref name=\"kent\"/> and in the next few days underwent a noticeable change in behaviour. There were \"symptoms of laughing and weeping, eloquence and silence.\" It is claimed that then \"he began to sing [[Sanskrit]] verses, a language of which it is alleged he had no prior knowledge.\"<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/> Doctors concluded his behaviour to be [[hysteria]].<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/> Concerned, his parents brought Sathya back home to Puttaparthi and took him to many priests, doctors and exorcists. One of the exorcists at [[Kadiri]], a town near Puttaparthi, went to the extent of torturing him with the aim of curing him; Sathya seemingly kept calm throughout the torture.\n\nOn 23 May 1940, Sathya called household members and reportedly materialised sugar candy (''[[prasad]])'' and flowers for them. His father became furious at seeing this, thinking his son was [[Spirit possession|bewitched]]. He took a stick and threatened to beat him if Sathya did not reveal who he really was, the young Sathya responded calmly and firmly \"I am Sai Baba\", a reference to [[Sai Baba of Shirdi]].<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/><ref name=\"kent\"/> This was the first time he proclaimed himself to be the reincarnation of Sai Baba of Shirdi\u2014a saint who became famous in the late 19th and early 20th centuries in [[Maharashtra]] and had died eight years before Sathya was born.<ref name=\"RichardWeiss\"/>\n\n===First mandir and development of Puttaparthi===\n\nIn 1944, a [[mandir]] for Sai Baba's devotees was built near the village of [[Puttaparthi]]. It is now referred to as the \"old mandir\".<ref name=\"bowen\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Sathya_Sai_Baba_Community_in_Bradfor.html?id=fJwQAAAACAAJ|title=The Sathya Sai Baba Community in Bradford: Its Origin and Development, Religious Beliefs and Practices|last=Bowen|first=David|date=1988|publisher=Department of Theology and Religious Studies, University of Leeds|isbn=9781871363029|language=en}}</ref> The construction of [[Prashanthi Nilayam]], the current ashram, began in 1948 and was completed in 1950.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/><ref name=\"bowen\"/> In 1954, Sai Baba established a small free general hospital in the village of Puttaparthi.<ref name=\"TheHinduNewspaper\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/features/saibaba/stories/2005112300270300.htm |title=Sri Sathya Sai 80th year of Advent |newspaper=The Hindu |date=23 November 2005|accessdate=10 January 2010|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> He won fame for his reputed mystical powers and ability to heal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/24/sri-sathya-sai-baba-dies|title=Sai Baba, spiritual guru to millions, dies at 85|author=Jason Burke|newspaper=the Guardian|date=2011-04-24}}</ref> In 1957 Sai Baba went on a North Indian temple tour.<ref name=\"Eade\"/>\n\n===Stroke, prediction of reincarnation and sole foreign tour===\n\nIn 1963, it was asserted that Sai Baba suffered a stroke and four severe heart attacks, which left him paralysed on one side. These events culminated in an event where he apparently healed himself in front of the thousands of people gathered in Prashanthi Nilayam who were then praying for his recovery.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/>\n\nOn recovering, Sai Baba announced that he would one day next be reborn as an incarnation named ''Prema Sai Baba'' in the neighbouring state of [[Karnataka]].<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/> He stated, \"I am Shiva-Sakthi, born in the [[gotra]] (lineage) of [[Bharadwaja]], according to a boon won by that sage from [[Shiva|Siva]] and [[Shakti|Sakthi]]. Siva was born in the gotra of that sage as Sai Baba of Shirdi; Shiva and Sakthi have incarnated as Myself in his gotra now; Sakthi alone will incarnate as the third Sai (Prema Sai Baba) in the same gotra in [[Mandya]] district of Karnataka State.\"<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/> He stated he would be born again eight years after his death at the age of 96, but died at the age of 84.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13180011 | work=BBC News | title=Satya Sai Baba, Indian guru, dies at 84 | date=24 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 June 1968, Sai Baba made his only overseas trip, to [[Kenya]] and [[Uganda]].\n\n===Later years===\n\nIn 1968, he established Dharmakshetra or the Sathyam Mandir in [[Mumbai]]. In 1973, he established the Shivam Mandir in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]]. On 19 January 1981, in [[Chennai]], he inaugurated the Sundaram Mandir.\n\nIn a [[1993 Murders in Prashanthi Nilayam|1993 incident]], four intruders armed with knives entered his bedroom, either as an assassination attempt or as part of a power struggle between his followers. Sai Baba was unharmed. During the scuffle and the police response, the intruders and two of Sai Baba's attendants were killed. The official investigation left questions unanswered.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/who-is-sri-sathya-sai-baba-101102|title=Who is Sri Sathya Sai Baba?|agency=Press Trust of India|date=24 April 2011|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/religion-obituaries/8471342/Sathya-Sai-Baba.html |title=Religion Obituaries; Satya Sai Baba |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=24 April 2011 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_sathya-sai-baba-escaped-murder-attempt_1535839 |title=Sathya Sai Baba escaped murder attempt|date=25 April 2011|last=Madhusoodan|first=M K |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1995, Sai Baba started a project to provide drinking water to 1.2 million people in the drought-prone Rayalaseema region in the [[Anantapur district]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/water-projects-cm-all-praise-for-satya-sai-trust/article27563258.ece|title=Water projects: CM all praise for Satya Sai Trust|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2004-02-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-10-09|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> In April 1999 he inaugurated the Ananda Nilayam Mandir in [[Madurai]], Tamil Nadu.\n\nIn 2001 he established another free super-speciality hospital in [[Bangalore]] to benefit the poor.\n\n===Old age, illness and death===\n\nIn 2003, Sai Baba suffered a fractured hip when a student standing on an iron stool slipped and the boy and stool both fell on him. After that he gave [[darshana]] from a car or his porte chair.<ref name=\"ibnlive.in.com82-2\">{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sai-baba-turns-82-is-still-going-strong/52860-3.html?from=search-relatedstories|title=Sai Baba turns 82, is still going strong|last=Balakrishnan|first=Deepa|authorlink=|date=23 November 2007|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|accessdate=6 January 2010}}</ref> After 2004, Sai Baba used a wheelchair and began to make fewer public appearances.\n\n{{Wikinews|Renowned Indian guru \u015ar\u012b Satya Sai Baba dies aged 84}}\nOn 28 March 2011, Sai Baba was admitted to the [[Sri Sathya Sai Super Speciality Hospital]] at Prashantigram at Puttaparthi, following respiration-related problems.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Sai Baba in stable condition: Hospital| newspaper = [[Hindustan Times]]| date = 5 April 2011| url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/Sai-Baba-in-stable-condition-Hospital/Article1-681433.aspx| accessdate = 24 April 2011| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110509014742/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Sai-Baba-in-stable-condition-Hospital/Article1-681433.aspx| archivedate = 9 May 2011| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Baba's health condition 'stable' | newspaper = [[The Times of India]] | date = 6 April 2011 | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-06/hyderabad/29388337_1_vital-parameters-condition-crrt | accessdate = 24 April 2011}}</ref> After nearly a month of hospitalisation, during which his condition progressively deteriorated, Sai Baba died on Sunday, 24 April at 7:40 IST, aged 84.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Spiritual leader Sathya Sai Baba passes away | newspaper = [[The Times of India]] | date = 24 April 2011 | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-24/india/29468573_1_sai-baba-sathya-sai-central-trust-puttaparthi   | accessdate = 24 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nSai Baba had predicted that he would die at age 96 and would remain healthy until then.<ref>{{cite book|title=Redemptive Encounters: Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition|last=Babb|first=Lawrence A.|publisher=University of California Press|year=1991|isbn=978-0-520-07636-5|location=|page=[https://archive.org/details/redemptiveencoun0000babb/page/166 166]|quote=His present incarnation, he says, ... He will die at the age of ninety-six, but his body will stay young until then.|url=https://archive.org/details/redemptiveencoun0000babb/page/166}}</ref> After he died, some devotees suggested that he was referring to that many [[lunar calendar|lunar years]], as counted by Telugu-speaking Hindus, rather than [[tropical year|solar years]],<ref>Mohammed Shafeeq. However it was soon  clearly shown that the lunar reckoning does not work.  Post. Durban: 27 April 2011. pg. 4</ref> and using the [[hindu calendar|Indian way]] of [[Ageing#Cultural variations|accounting for age]], which counts the year to come as part of the person's life.<ref>Sri Philip M. Prasad, Malayalam Daily. Kerala, India: 25 April 2011. \"What Baba has foretold was indeed correct. According to the Roman calendar he has completed 85 years. But one can note that generally in all of Baba's discourses Baba had been referring to the star (lunar) basis in calculations. In Indian astrology there are 27 stars in a month starting with Aswathy and ending with Revathy. Accordingly a year of 12 months is composed of 324 days. Sai Baba was born on 23 November 1925. From that day till his death day 24 April 2011 there were a total of 33,899 days. If this is divided with 324, we get 95 years and 54 days. Accordingly, under the star basis of calculation he was in his 96th year having completed 54 days when he left his physical body.\"</ref> Other devotees have spoken of his anticipated [[resurrection]], [[reincarnation]] or [[wakefulness|awakening]].<ref>''The Hindustan Times'', New Delhi: 25 April 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Narayan |first1=Sreejith |title=Sai, Thy Kingdom Come | year = 2012| isbn = 978-1-62314-842-3 | url =http://www.saikingdom.com}}</ref>\n\n====Funeral and mourning====\n\nHis body lay in state for two days and was [[Burial|buried]] with full state honours on 27 April 2011.<ref name=\"news9\">News 9, 24 April 2011, 16:00 IST</ref> An estimated 500,000 people attended the burial, among them the Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]], [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] president [[Sonia Gandhi]], then Gujarat Chief Minister [[Narendra Modi]] (India's Present Prime Minister), Cricketer [[Sachin Tendulkar]] and [[Union Minister]]s [[S. M. Krishna]] and [[Ambika Soni]], as well as other political leaders and prominent figures.<ref>{{Cite news | title =Sathya Sai Baba gets a tearful farewell at his Puttaparthi home | newspaper=[[India Today]] | date = 27 April 2011 | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/sathya-sai-baba-last-rites-in-puttaparthi/1/136399.html|accessdate = 27 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia/2011/04/201142452416203714.html |title=Indian guru Sai Baba dies in hospital \u2013 Central & South Asia |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date= |accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_sathya-sai-baba-buried-in-puttaparthi_1536633 |title=Sathya Sai Baba buried in Puttaparthi |publisher=DNA |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/final-farewell-to-sathya-sai-baba-today/150310-3.html|title=Tearful farewell to Sathya Sai Baba |publisher=[[CNN-IBN]] |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nPolitical leaders who offered their condolences included the then Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]],<ref name=\"news9\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirchi9.com/news/2011/04/24/l-k-advani-reaction-on-sathya-sai-babas-death-tv9/|title=L.K.Advani Reaction on Sathya Sai Baba's Death :TV9 \u2013 Mirchi 9 \u2013 Telugu News &#124; Andhra News &#124; Hyderabad &#124; Andhra &#124; India &#124; Brain &#124; Studies &#124; University|publisher=Mirchi9.com|accessdate=24 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323040616/http://www.mirchi9.com/news/2011/04/24/l-k-advani-reaction-on-sathya-sai-babas-death-tv9/|archivedate=23 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://70mmonline.com/WatchMovie.aspx?movieid=9086&movieName=L.K.Advani%20Reaction%20on%20Sathya%20Sai%20Baba's%20Death|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018100215/http://70mmonline.com/WatchMovie.aspx?movieid=9086&movieName=L.K.Advani%20Reaction%20on%20Sathya%20Sai%20Baba's%20Death|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 October 2011|title=L.K.Advani Reaction on Sathya Sai Baba's Death, TV9 \u2013 L.K.Advani Reaction on Sathya Sai Baba's Death at|publisher=70mmonline.com|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref> Sri Lankan President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/news/2011/04/26/world-has-lost-great-spiritual-leader-sri-lankan-president-mahinda-rajapaksa|title=World has lost a great spiritual leader \u2013 Sri Lankan President Mahinda Rajapaksa|work=asiantribune.com}}</ref> and the [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://news.outlookindia.com/item.aspx?719929|title = Dalai Lama Mourns Sri Sathya Sai Baba's Death\n|publisher = outlookindia.com|date = 25 April 2011|accessdate = 29 May 2011}}</ref> Cricketer [[Sachin Tendulkar]], whose birthday was that day, cancelled his birthday celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketnext.in.com/news/sachin-mourns-sai-babas-death-on-his-bday/56827-13.html|title=Sachin mourns SaiBaba death on his b'day|date=24 April 2011|work=IBNLive}}</ref> ''[[The Hindu]]'' newspaper reported that \"Sri Sathya Sai Baba's propagation of spiritualism and preaching of Hindu philosophy never came in the way of his commitment to secular beliefs.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article1764337.ece?homepage=true | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=A secular spiritual leader | date=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Government of [[Karnataka]] declared 25 and 26 April as [[day of mourning|days of mourning]] and Andhra Pradesh declared 25, 26, and 27 April as days of mourning.<ref name=\"news9\"/>\n[[File:Sathya Sai Baba Samadhi at Puttaparthi, India.jpg|thumb|250px|Swamigal's Prashanthi Nilayam at Puttaparthi]]\n\n==Sathya Sai Organisation==\n{{Main|Sathya Sai Organisation}}\nThe Sathya Sai Organisation (or Sri Sathya Sai [[Selfless service|Seva]] Organization) was founded in the 1960s by Sathya Sai Baba.<ref name=\"srisaiorg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srisathyasai.org.in/Pages/Sai_Organisations/Sai_Organisations.htm|title=SSSCT- Sri Sathya Sai Seva Organisation|work=srisathyasai.org.in}}</ref> Initially called the \"Sri Sathya Sai Seva Samithi\",<ref name=\"saiindia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saibabaofindia.com/sai_baba_centers.htm|title=Sai Baba Of India-Sri Sathya Sai Baba Centers- Sai Baba organisation worldwide|work=saibabaofindia.com}}</ref> it was established \"to enable its members to undertake service activities as a means to spiritual advancement.\"<ref name=\"srisaiorg\"/>\n\nThe Sathya Sai Organisation reports that there are an estimated 1,200 Sathya Sai Baba Centres in 114 countries.<ref name=\"TheStarOnline84\">{{cite web |url=http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2009/12/3/north/5212802&sec=North |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521155709/http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=%2F2009%2F12%2F3%2Fnorth%2F5212802&sec=North |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 May 2011 |title=Sai Baba turns 84 |publisher=Thestar.com.my |date=3 December 2009 |accessdate=6 January 2010  }}</ref><ref name=\"SathyaSaiNumbers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sathyasai.org/organize/content.htm#SaiOrg|title=The Sai Organization: Numbers to Sai Centres and Names of Countries|publisher=Sathyasai.org|accessdate=6 January 2010}}</ref> However, the number of active Sai Baba followers is hard to determine.<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\" /> Estimates vary from 6 million<ref>[http://www.adherents.com/Na/Na_581.html#3510 Adherents] cites [[George Chryssides|Chryssides, George]]. ''Exploring New Religions''. London, UK: Cassells (1999) (10 million)<br />*Brown, Mick (2000-10-28). \"Divine Downfall\". Daily Telegraph. https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/main.jhtml?xml=/health/2000/10/28/tlbaba28.xml. Retrieved 2007-03-12<br />*Edwards, Linda (2001). A Brief Guide to Beliefs: Ideas, Theologies, Mysteries, and Movements. Westminster John Knox Press. {{ISBN|0-664-22259-5}}.</ref> up to nearly 100 million.<ref>''[[The Economist]]'', [http://www.economist.com/node/18678803 \"Sai Baba\"], 14 May 2011, p. 110.</ref> In India itself, Sai Baba drew followers predominantly from the [[upper-middle-class]], the urban sections of society who have the \"most wealth, education and exposure to Western ideas.\"<ref name=\"UrbanHugh74\">{{cite journal|last=Urban|first=Hugh B.|author-link=Hugh Urban|year=2003|title=Avatar for Our Age: Sathya Sai Baba and the Cultural Contradictions of Late Capitalism|journal=[[Religion (journal)|Religion]]|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|volume=33|issue=1|page=74|doi=10.1016/S0048-721X(02)00080-5|issn=0048-721X|eissn=1096-1151}}</ref> In 2002, he claimed to have followers in 178 countries.<ref name=\"nyt1dec2002\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/01/world/a-friend-in-india-to-all-the-world.html?pagewanted=1|title=A Friend in India to All the World|last=Bradsher|first=Keith|date=1 December 2002|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Palmer97-98\">Palmer, Norris W. \"Baba's World\". In: {{cite book|last=Forsthoefel|first=Thomas A.|last2=Humes|first2=Cynthia Ann (eds.)|title=Gurus in America|place=Albany, New York|publisher=State University of New York Press|year=2005|pages=97\u201398|isbn=978-0-7914-6574-5}}</ref>\n\nSathya Sai Baba founded a large number of schools and colleges, hospitals, and other charitable institutions in India and abroad, the net financial capital of which is usually estimated at Rs. 400&nbsp;billion (US$9 billion).<ref>\n{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/sathya-sai-baba-passes-away-leaves-behind-rs-40000-cr-worth-empire-with-no-clear-succession-plan/articleshow/8075953.cms|title=Sathya Sai Baba passes away, leaves behind Rs 40,000-cr worth empire with no clear succession plan\n|newspaper=[[The Economic Times|Economic Times]] | date=25 April 2011 |quote=Sai Baba leaves behind a wide network of charitable institutions, hospitals, schools, colleges, which some estimate to be worth about Rs 40,000 crore}}\n</ref><ref name=it>{{cite magazine|title=Up in the Heir: The secret world of Sathya Sai Baba's Rs 40,000 cr empire |author=Amarnath K. Menon |magazine=[[India Today]] |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/story/sathya-sai-baba-health-scare-assets-transition/1/135354.html |date=25 April 2011 |accessdate=9 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424073421/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/story/sathya-sai-baba-health-scare-assets-transition/1/135354.html |archivedate=24 April 2011 }}</ref><ref name=dh>{{cite news| title =Sai Baba's death leaves question mark on Rs 40,000 crore empire| author =Indo-Asian News Service| newspaper =    [[Deccan Herald]]| url =          http://www.deccanherald.com/content/156224/sai-babas-death-leaves-question.html| date = 24 April 2011\n|accessdate =9 June 2011| author-link =Indo-Asian News Service}}</ref> However, estimates as high as 1.4 trillion rupees (about US$31.5bn) have also been made.<ref>{{cite news| title =Sathya Sai Baba trust worth Rs 1.4 lakh crore?|publisher =[[CNN-IBN]]| url =http://ibnlive.in.com/news/sathya-sai-baba-trust-worth-rs-14-lakh-crore/150273-3.html| date =26 April 2011| accessdate =9 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter his death, questions about the manner in which the finances of the organisation were going to be managed led to speculations of impropriety, with some reports suggesting that suitcases containing cash and/or gold had been removed from his personal lodgings.<ref name=\"dh\" /><ref>{{cite news| title =What's inside Sathya Sai's personal chamber?| publisher =    [[Zee News]]\n|url =http://zeenews.india.com/news710182.html| date =2 June 2011| accessdate =9 June 2011}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news| title =Trust hesitant on unlocking Sai Babas residence| author =Express News Service| publisher = [[CNN-IBN]]| url =http://ibnlive.in.com/news/trust-hesitant-on-unlocking-sai-babas-residence/155644-60-114.html\n|date =31 May 2011| accessdate =   9 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 2011, officials from the Sri Sathya Sai Central Trust opened his private residence in the presence of government, bank and tax department officials.<ref>Deccan Herald, Tuesday 17 June. 2011, \"Huge amount of gold, silver, cash found in Sai Baba's Chamber\" http://www.deccanherald.com/content/169535/huge-amount-gold-silver-cash.html.</ref> In the private residence, which had been sealed since his death, they inventoried 98&nbsp;kg of gold ornaments, approximate value Rs 21 [[crores]] (US$4.7m), 307&nbsp;kg of silver ornaments, approximate value Rs 16&nbsp;million (US$0.36m), and Rs 116&nbsp;million (US$2.6m) in cash. The cash was deposited into the Sai Trust's account at the State Bank of India with payment of government taxes (thus transferring them from religious gifts to Trust assets.) The gold and other items were inventoried, assessed, and placed in secure storage. In July, district authorities inventoried an additional Rs 7.7&nbsp;million (US$0.17m) in valuables in another 4 rooms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-03/india/29733031_1_satya-sai-baba-precious-metals-diamond-ring|title=Assets worth Rs 77L seized at Sai ashram|date=3 July 2011|newspaper=Times of India}}</ref> The total value of these items is believed to exceed 7.8 million US dollars.<ref name=\"hindustan times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Treasure-island-Sai-Baba-s-gold-trove/Article1-710596.aspx|title=Treasure island: Sai Baba's gold trove|date=17 June 2011|publisher=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref> Also inventoried at Yajurmandir were thousands of pure silk sarees, dhotis, shirts, 500 pairs of shoes, dozens of bottles of perfume and hairspray, watches, a large number of silver and gold \"mangala sutrams\", and precious stones such as diamonds. There were also 750 saffron and white robes of the type Sai Baba wore.<ref name=\"500 pairs\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110618/jsp/nation/story_14130452.jsp|title=Open sesame! Baba & his chamber of secrets|author=G.S. Radhakrishna|date=17 June 2011|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph of India]]|location=Calcutta, India}} and [http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110618/images/18zzsaibababig.jpg this graphic]</ref> In July 2011, a similar opening of his Bangalore-area ashram tallied 6&nbsp;kg of gold coins and jewellery, 245&nbsp;kg of silver articles and Rs 8&nbsp;million in cash. These items and goods are believed to have been donated over the years by Sai Baba's devotees from all over the world as religious gifts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-21/bangalore/29798927_1_brindavan-revenue-officials-ashram|title=Three-day count at Baba's ashram yields treasure|date=21 July 2011|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/178661/perfumes-sarees-form-sai-babas.html,|title=Perfumes, sarees form Sai Baba's inventory|work=Deccan Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:Sri Sathya Sai Project 1999 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|A 1999 stamp devoted to the Sri Sathya Sai Water Supply Project]]\n[[File:Sathya Sai Baba 2013 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Sathya Sai Baba on a 2013 stamp of India]]\nOn 23 November 1999, the Department of Posts, [[Government of India]], released a postage stamp and a postal cover in recognition of the service rendered by Sai Baba in addressing the problem of providing safe drinking water to the rural masses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srisathyasai.org.in/Pages/Service_Projects/Anantapur.htm |title=SSSCT-Service Projects \u2013 Water Supply \u2013 Anantapur |publisher=Srisathyasai.org.in |date=23 November 1999 |accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> Another commemorative stamp was released on the occasion of what would have been his 88th birthday during November 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/postal-stamp-on-sathya-sai-baba-released/article5385073.ece|title=Postal stamp on Sathya Sai Baba released|date=24 November 2013|work=The Hindu|location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Postal-department-to-release-stamp-on-Sathya-Sai-Baba/articleshow/26168869.cms|title=Postal department to release stamp on Sathya Sai Baba \u2013 The Times of India|work=The Times Of India}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, an event was held in [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Chennai|Chennai Nehru Stadium]] organised by the Chennai Citizens' Conclave to thank Sai Baba for the 2&nbsp;billion water project which brought water from the [[River Krishna]] in Andhra Pradesh to Chennai city. Four chief ministers attended the function.<ref name=\"Chennai Visit\">[http://www.indianexpress.com/story/21444.html Felicitation for Water Project] Indian Express.</ref>\n\n==Ashrams and mandirs==\n\n===Prasanthi Nilayam===\n[[File:PrashantiNilayam1.jpg|left|thumb|Puttaparthi, A.P.]]\n{{Main|Prasanthi Nilayam}}\n[[File:Chaitanya Jyothi Museum, Prashanthi Nilayam, India.jpg|thumb|Chaitanya Jyoti Museum devoted to the life and teachings of Sathya Sai Baba]]\nPuttaparthi, where Sai Baba was born and lived, was originally a small, remote South Indian village in Andhra Pradesh. Now there is an extensive university complex, a speciality hospital, and two museums: the ''Sanathana Samskruti'' or Eternal Heritage Museum, sometimes called the Museum of All Religions, and the ''Chaitanya Jyoti'', devoted exclusively to the life and teachings of Sai Baba; the latter has won several international awards for its architectural design.<ref name=\"TheStar2005-04-02\">{{cite web |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=M. |title=Enlightening experience in India |publisher=The Star Online |date=2 April 2005 |url=http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=/2005/4/2/features/9982154&sec=features |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050412101614/http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=%2F2005%2F4%2F2%2Ffeatures%2F9982154&sec=features |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 April 2005 |accessdate=6 January 2010  }}</ref> There is also a planetarium, a railway station, a hill-view stadium, an administrative building, an airport, an indoor sports stadium and more.<ref>Places to see at Puttaparthi. [http://www.sathyasai.org/ashrams/prasanthi/outsideinterest.html Available online]</ref> High-ranking Indian politicians such as the former president [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]], former prime minister [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], Andhra Pradesh former chief minister [[Konijeti Rosaiah]] and [[Karnataka]] chief minister [[B. S. Yeddyurappa]] have been official guests at the ashram in Puttaparthi.<ref>''The Hindu'', \"A 5-point recipe for happiness\" 24 November 2006 [http://www.hindu.com/2006/11/24/stories/2006112405400400.htm Available online]</ref><ref>''The Hindu'', \"Warm welcome to PM at Puttaparthi\",12 February 2004 [http://www.hinduonnet.com/2004/02/12/stories/2004021203690600.htm Available online]</ref> It was reported that well over a million people attended Sai Baba's 80th birthday celebration, including 13,000 delegates from India and 180 other countries.<ref>''Deccan Herald'', \"Sathya Sai's birthday celebrations on\" by Terry Kennedy, 23 November 2005, [http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/nov232005/national1724520051122.asp Available online] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070501184330/http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/nov232005/national1724520051122.asp |date=1 May 2007 }}</ref>{{Citation needed |date=October 2013}}\n\n[[File:Hill in Prashanthi Nilayam with statues of Hanuman, Krishna, Shirdi Sai Baba, Shiva, Buddha, Christ, Zarathustra.jpg|thumb|Hill in Prashanthi Nilayam with statues of Hanuman, Krishna, Shirdi Sai Baba, Shiva, Buddha, Christ, Zarathustra.]]\n\nSai Baba resided much of the time in his main [[ashram]], ''Prashanthi Nilayam'' (Abode of Highest Peace), at Puttaparthi. In the summer he often left for his other ashram, ''Brindavan'', in Kadugodi, [[Whitefield, India|Whitefield]], a town on the outskirts of [[Bangalore]]. Occasionally he visited his Sai Shruti ashram in [[Kodaikanal]].<ref>The ashrams of Sathya Sai Baba. Referenced from the official Sathya Sai Organization website, [http://www.sathyasai.org/ashrams/content.html Available online]</ref>\n\n==Characteristics, beliefs and practices of devotees==\n{{Main|Sathya Sai Baba movement}}\nReliable sources often describe Sai Baba's following as a \"movement\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kent|first=Alexandra|date=1999|title=UNITY IN DIVERSITY: Portraying the Visions of the Sathya Sai Baba Movement of Malaysia|jstor=40800435|journal=Crossroads: An Interdisciplinary Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|volume=13\u20132|issue=2|pages=29\u201351}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sahoo|first=Ajaya Kumar|date=2013|title=Reconstructing Religious and Cultural Identity of Indians in the Diaspora: The Role of Sri Sathya Sai Baba Movement|jstor=23621024|journal=Sociological Bulletin|volume= 62| issue =  1 (January\u2013April 2013)|pages= 23\u201339|doi=10.1177/0038022920130102}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.americamagazine.org/content/all-things/death-god-man-sai-baba-dies-85|title=Death of a God-man? Sai Baba Dies at 85|last=Clooney|first=Francis X.|date=2011|work=America Magazine|access-date=}}</ref> A study by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) states \"A worldwide mass religious movement is growing around the Indian holy man and  miracle worker, Sathya Sai Baba.\" Later noting, \"The Sai Baba movement is likely to eventually become another worldwide religion.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP96-00792R000400280002-2.pdf|title=Cultural Trends Study \u2013 India's Sai Baba Movement|last=CIA|date=|website=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/cia-rdp96-00792r000400280002-2|access-date=}}</ref> Among scholars, we find it referred to often as either a \"[[New religious movement|New Religious Movement]]\" (NRM)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pereira|first=Shane N.|title=A New Religious Movement in Singapore: Syncretism and Variation in the Sathya Sai Baba Movement|jstor=23677933|journal= Asian Journal of Social Science|volume= 36| issue =  2|pages= 250\u2013270|year=2008|doi=10.1163/156853108X298699}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ekacha|first=Sanitsuda|date=2001|title=Keeping the Faith: Thai Buddhism at the Crossroads|journal=Nova Religio: The Journal of Alternative and Emergent Religions|volume= 9| issue = 2|pages=126\u2013128|doi=10.1525/nr.2005.9.2.126}}</ref> or as a  [[cult]],<ref name=das15/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Swallow|first1=D.A.|title=Living Saints and Their Devotees|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f1gkAQAAIAAJ&q=sathya+sai+baba+cult&dq=sathya+sai+baba+cult|date=1976|publisher=[PhD thesis summary published in ''Research in Social Anthropology, 1975\u20131980: A Register of Theses Accepted for Higher Degrees at British Universities, 1975\u20131980'', pp. 385\u2013386]}}</ref> it appears it is not immune to what Robbins and Zablocki, two social science researchers, call \"the divisive polarization, which, at least until recently, has plagued the academic study of religious movements.\" referencing a wide divide of two camps within academia, each preferring one term over the other (i.e. NRM or cult) for such groups';<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pJ9Nmc25xNAC&pg=PA515&dq=0802081886#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Misunderstanding Cults: Searching for Objectivity in a Controversial Field|last=Robbins & Zablocki|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=2001|isbn=978-0-8020-4373-3|location=|pages=3\u20135}}</ref> It's been noted by Eugene Gallagher, that in more modern times \"'New Religious movement', on the other hand, is a classification preferred by most academics, who see 'cult' as a pejorative term and intend to replace it with a more neutral label.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gallagher|first=Eugene|date=November 2007 \u2013 February 2008|title=\"Cults\" and \"New Religious Movements\"|jstor=10.1086/524210|journal=History of Religions, University of Chicago Press|volume= 47| issue =  2/3|pages=205\u2013220|doi=10.1086/524210}}</ref> It is regarded by most scholars to be of Hindu persuasion.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Babb|first1=L. A.|editor1-last=Hawley|editor1-first=J.S.|title=Saints and Virtues|date=1987|publisher=University of California Press|location=London (UK)|isbn=978-0-520-06163-7|pages=168\u2013186|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RGv2wOUl0pMC&dq|chapter=Sathya Sai Baba's Saintly Play}}</ref><ref>Alexandra Kent Divinity and diversity: a Hindu revitalization movement in Malaysia, NIAS, 2005</ref><ref>Handoo, Jawaharlal in ''Asian Folklore Studies'', Vol. 48, No. 2 (1989), pp. 326\u201332 reviewing Lawrence A. Babb's book ''Redemptive Encounters. Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition'' [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1177938 page 1]</ref><ref>Nagel, Alexandra (note: Nagel is a critical former follower) \"De Sai Paradox: Tegenstrijdigheden van en rondom Sathya Sai Baba\"/\"The Sai Paradox contradictions of and surrounding Sathya Sai Baba\" from the magazine \"Religieuze Bewegingen in Nederland, 'Sekten' \"/\"Religious movements in the Netherlands, 'Cults/Sects' \", 1994, nr. 29. published by the [[Free University of Amsterdam]] press, (1994) {{ISBN|90-5383-341-2}}<br> Dutch original: \"Ofschoon Sai Baba gezegd heeft mensen van allerlei religieuze gezindten te helpen terug te gaan naar oude waarden en normen, en ofschoon zijn logo de symbolen van de andere grote godsdiensten bevat, is de sfeer rondom Sai Baba duidelijk hindoe\u00efstisch gekleurd. Alle moslim-elementen bijv. waarvan verondersteld zou kunnen worden dat hij die zou hebben meegenomen uit zijn leven als Sai Baba van Shirdi, heeft hij laten vallen. Het enig echt herkenbare wat hij van Shirdi Baba nog heeft, is het veelvuldig gebruik van as, \u2013 wat hij dan niet uit een dhuni haalt zoals Shirdi Baba deed, maar materialiseert (of tevoorschijn goochelt)\"</ref>\n\nSai Baba claimed to be the reincarnation of Sai Baba of Shirdi, and his followers considered him to be the [[Avatar]] of [[Shiva]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WA12nHRtmAwC&pg=PA307 |author=Chryssides, George D. |title=Historical dictionary of new religious movements |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2012|isbn=9780810861947 }}</ref> Sai Baba of Shirdi was known to combine Islamic and Hindu teachings; still Charles S. J. White, of [[The American University]] at Washington D.C., noted of Sathya Sai Baba in 1972, that \"there is no discernible Muslim influence.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=White|first1=Charles S. J.|title=The Sai Baba Movement: Approaches to the Study of India Saints|journal=The Journal of Asian Studies|date=1972|volume=31|issue=4|pages=863\u2013878|doi=10.2307/2052105|jstor=2052105}}</ref> Stephanie Tallings, in The Harvard international Review, noted Sai Baba's following is drawn from people of all religions, ethnicities, and social classes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tallings|first=Stephanies|date=Summer 2000|title=Avatar of Stability: Sai Baba's Teachings|url=https://www.jstor.org/publisher/hir|journal=Harvard International Review|volume= 22| issue =  2|pages=14\u201315|via=}}</ref> Lawrence A. Babb, of the Amherst College in Massachusetts, labelled Sai Baba movement as a cult in the 1980s, calling it \"deeply and authentically Hindu...\" and noted, \"The most striking feature of this cult, however, is the extremely strong emphasis given to the miraculous.\"<ref name=\"babb83\" /> However, a scholarly review claims Babb misapplies the word \u201ccult\u201d, responding, \"the so-called 'cult' of Satya Sai Baba seems to possess all such characteristics which are, according to the author, central to a religious movement.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Handoo|first=Jawaharlal|date=1989|title=Reviewed Work: Redemptive Encounters. Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition by Lawrence A. Babb|url=http://asianethnology.org/downloads/ae/pdf/a759.pdf|journal=Asian Folklore Studies|volume= 48| issue =  2|page=327|via=}}</ref> Deborah A. Swallow, of the University of Cambridge, referred to it as a cult and said that the \"ritual and theology, then, unlike Sai Baba [of Shirdi]'s, is distinctly Hindu in form and content.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Swallow|first1=D. A.|title=Ashes and Powers: Myth, Rite and Miracle in an Indian God-Man's Cult|journal=Modern Asian Studies|date=2008|volume=16|issue=1|pages=123\u2013158|doi=10.1017/S0026749X0000072X|jstor=312277}}</ref> But John D. Kelly, a professor of anthropology at the University of Chicago, wrote about Hindu missions in Fiji that the Sathya Sai Organization (which is part of the movement) rejected the label Hindu. According to Kelly, they see their founder as the \"living synthesis of the world's religious traditions\" and prefer to be classified as an [[interfaith]] movement. But he observed that Sai Baba mission is a Hindu mission as active as Christian or Muslim missions.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kelly|first1=J.D.|editor1-last=van der Veer|editor1-first=P.|title=Nation and Migration: The Politics of Space in the South Asian Diaspora|date=1995|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Philadelphia (US)|isbn=978-0-8122-1537-3|pages=43\u201372|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bvTHlLRZL8UC&dq|chapter=Bhakti and Postcolonial Politics: Hindu Missions to Fiji}}</ref> In a 2001 scholarly book Tulasi Srinivas, notes, \"The Sathya Sai global civil religious movement incorporates Hindu and Muslim practices, Buddhist, Christian, and Zoroastrian influences, and \"New Age\"-style rituals and beliefs.\u2019 And in the appendix of the book (p. 349) lists 10 scholarly authors/researchers in both Europe and America who all refer to it as a New Religious Movement (NRM).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Winged Faith: Rethinking Globalization and Religious Pluralism through the Sathya Sai Movement|last=Srinivas|first=Tulasi|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=June 2010|isbn=9780231149334|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSai Baba was known for his quote \"Love All, Serve All. Help Ever, Hurt Never.\"<ref name=\"Leslie-Chaden2004\">{{cite book|author=Charlene Leslie-Chaden|title=A compendium of the teachings of Sri Sathya Sai Baba|url=http://puttaparthi.info/shopping/shp/bookdetail.asp?itemid=B1001|accessdate=24 April 2011|year=2004|publisher=Sai Towers Publishing|page=526|isbn=978-81-7899-042-2}} {{self-published source|date=April 2011}}</ref>{{Self-published inline|date=April 2011}}<ref name=\"Architectural digest\">{{cite book|title=Architectural digest|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YcxUAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=24 April 2011|date=1 May 1994|publisher=Conde Nast Publications}}</ref> Internationally, his devotees gather daily, or weekly on Sundays or Thursdays or both, for [[bhajans|devotional songs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sathyasai.ca/ |title=Sri Sathya Sai Baba Organization in Canada \u2013 Home Page |publisher=Sathyasai.ca |date=1 May 2006 |accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> prayer,<ref name=\"saius\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110727120609/http://us.sathyasai.org/resources/06oct15CenterGuidelines12.pdf Guidelines for AMERICAN SATHYA SAI BABA CENTERS]. The Sathya Sai Baba Central Council of the United States of America (2006)</ref> spiritual meditation, service to the community (Seva),<ref name=\"saito\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sathyasaitoronto.org/ |title=The Sri Sathya Sai Baba Centre of Toronto \u2013 York |publisher=Sathyasaitoronto.org |date= |accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> and to participate in \"Education in Human Values\" (SSEHV)<ref name=\"saius\"/> known as \"''Bal Vikas''\" (Blossoming of the Child).\n\nFollowers believed in seeking the spiritual benefit of Sai Baba's ''[[darsana|darshan]]'', scheduled for morning and afternoon each day. Sai Baba would interact with people, accept letters, materialise and distribute [[vibhuti]] (sacred ash) or call groups or individuals for interviews. Devotees considered it a great privilege to have an interview and sometimes a single person, group or family was invited for a private interview for answers to spiritual questions and general guidance.<ref name=\"kent\"/>\n\nThe ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'' in 2001 reported that Sai Baba told his adherents not to browse the internet.<ref name=\"VS\">{{Cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/staff-blogs/sai-baba-holy-man-sex-abuser-both|title=Sai Baba: Holy man? Sex abuser? Both?|date=2011-04-26|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n=== Criticism ===\nAccusations<!-- Please do not change this wording, this has been agreed on the talk page. If you don't agree on it read the discussion there. --> against Sai Baba by his critics over the years have included sleight of hand, sexual abuse, money laundering, fraud in the performance of service projects, and murder.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/><ref name=Palmer116/>\n\nIn 1972 [[Abraham Kovoor]] made the first public criticism of Sai Baba<ref name=\"srisathyasaibabaandthepress\">Ruhela S.P., ''Sri Sathya Sai Baba and the Press'', pp. 1\u20135, 1997 {{ISBN|81-7533-041-4}}</ref> when he looked into a claim publicly narrated by one devotee<ref name=\"srisathyasaibabaandthepress\" /> that Sai Baba had created a new model of a [[Seiko]] watch, and found the claim to be untrue.<ref name=\"sathyasaibabasgrace\">Ruhela S.P., ''How to Receive Sri Sathya Sai Baba's Grace'', pp. 277, 2006 {{ISBN|81-7182-089-1}}</ref><ref name=OutlookSingh>{{cite web|title=The Spell Breaker|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?262445|publisher=Outlook|accessdate=16 October 2013|author=Rahul Singh|date=2 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1976, [[Hosur Narasimhaiah|Hossur Narasimhaiah]], a physicist, rationalist and then vice-chancellor of [[Bangalore University]], founded and chaired a committee \"to rationally and scientifically investigate miracles and other verifiable superstitions\". Narasimhaiah wrote Sai Baba three widely publicised letters challenging him to perform his miracles under controlled conditions. The letters were ignored.<ref name=\"haraldsson204\">Haraldson, ''op. cit'', pp&nbsp;204\u2013205</ref> Sai Baba said that he ignored Narasimhaiah's challenge because he felt that a scientific approach to spiritual issues was improper, adding that \"Science must confine its inquiry only to things belonging to the human senses, while spiritualism transcends the senses. If you want to understand the nature of spiritual power you can do so only through the path of spirituality and not science. What science has been able to unravel is merely a fraction of the cosmic phenomena&nbsp;...\"<ref name=\"blitz\">Interview given by Sai Baba to [[R. K. Karanjia]] of ''Blitz'' news magazine in September 1976 [http://www.saibaba.ws/articles/interviewwithjournalistsept1976.htm Available online]</ref> Narasimhaiah's committee was dissolved in August 1977. Narasimhaiah held the fact that Sai Baba ignored his letters to be an indication that his miracles were fraudulent.<ref>Haraldsson, pp 209</ref> As a result of this episode, a public debate raged for several months in Indian newspapers.<ref>Haraldsson, ''op. cit.'', pp. 206</ref>\n\nIndian rationalist [[Basava Premanand]], who began campaigning against Sai Baba in 1976, unsuccessfully attempted to sue him in 1986 for violations of the [[Gold Control Act]], citing Sai Baba's purported materialisations of gold objects. When the case was dismissed, Premanand unsuccessfully appealed on the grounds that claimed spiritual power is not a defence recognised in law.<ref name=bbca1>{{cite news|author=Tanya Datta|title=Sai Baba: Goan or con man?|date=17 June 2004|work=[[BBC News]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/this_world/3813469.stm | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nA 1995 TV documentary ''Guru Busters'', produced by filmmaker [[Robert Eagle (writer and director)|Robert Eagle]] for the UK's [[Channel 4]], accused Sai Baba of faking his materialisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eagletv.co.uk/home/guru.htm |title=Eagle & Eagle |publisher=Eagletv.co.uk |date= |accessdate=7 January 2010}} [http://www.eagletv.co.uk/home/videos/Saimagic.mov Clip]</ref> The clip from the film was mentioned in the ''[[Deccan Chronicle]]'', on 23 November 1992, in a front-page headline \"DD Tape Unveils Baba Magic\".<ref>Haraldsson, ''op. cit.'', pp.&nbsp;295\u2013301</ref>\n\nIn 1998, British journalist Mick Brown stated in his book ''The Spiritual Tourist'' that in his opinion claims of Sai Baba resurrecting American devotee Walter Cowan in 1971 were probably untrue.<ref name=\"spiritualtourist\">Mick Brown, ''The Spiritual Tourist'', 1998, Bloomsbury Publishing, {{ISBN|1-58234-034-X}} \"In the House of God\", pp.&nbsp;73\u201374</ref> His opinion was based on letters from the attending doctors presented in the magazine ''[[Indian Skeptic]]'', published by Basava Premanand.<ref name=\"spiritualtourist\"/><ref>Hislop, John S. ''My Baba and I'' 1985 published by Birth Day Publishing Company, San Diego, California {{ISBN|0-9600958-8-8}}, \"The Resurrection of Walter Cowan\", pages&nbsp;28\u201331</ref> Brown also related, in the same book, his experiences with manifestations of ''vibuthi'' from Sai Baba's pictures in houses in London, which he felt were not fraudulent or the result of trickery.<ref name=\"touristmiracle\">Brown Mick, ''The Spiritual Tourist'', \"The Miracle in North London\", pp.&nbsp;29\u201330, 1998 {{ISBN|158234034X}}</ref> Brown wrote with regards to Sai Baba's claims of omniscience, that \"sceptics have produced documentation clearly showing discrepancies between Baba's reading of historical events and biblical prophecies, and the established accounts.\"<ref name=\"spiritualtourist\"/>\n\n===Allegations of  abuse===\nIn January 2002, a documentary produced by Denmark's national television and radio broadcast company, [[Danish radio|Danmarks Radio]] (DR), called ''Seduced By Sai Baba'', analysed videos of public manifestations of Sai Baba and suggested that they could be explained as [[sleight of hand]].<ref name=\"seduced\">{{cite video|people=\u00d8yvind Kyr\u00f8, Steen Jensen |title=Seduced by Sai Baba |medium=Documentary |publisher=[[DR (broadcaster)|DR]] |date=2002 |url=http://dr.dk/Salg/DRsales/Programmes/Documentary/Society_and_Social/20070629133445_3_1_3_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204010039/http://www.dr.dk/Salg/DRsales/Programmes/Documentary/Society_and_Social/20070629133445_3_1_3_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1_1.htm |archivedate=4 February 2010 }}</ref> The documentary also presented interviews with Alaya Rahm, former devotee of Sathya Sai Baba, where he alleged abuse by Sathya Sai Baba.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/> As a result, in 2002 the parliament of the United Kingdom discussed the possible danger to male children of British families intending to visit the ashram of Sathya Sai Baba in case of individual audiences with the guru.<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2001-02/886] UK Parliament official web site</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[BBC]] produced a documentary titled ''The Secret Swami'' as part of its series \"The World Uncovered\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/this_world/3791921.stm |title=Programmes &#124; This World &#124; Secret Swami |work=BBC News |date=11 June 2004 |accessdate=7 January 2010}}</ref> One central theme of the BBC documentary was again Alaya Rahm's sexual abuse allegations against Sathya Sai Baba.<ref name=bbcd>{{cite video|people=Eamon Hardy, Tanya Datta|title=Secret Swami|medium=Documentary|publisher=BBC News|date=2004 |time= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/this_world/3791921.stm | accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref> This documentary interviewed him together with Mark Roche, who had spent 25 years of his life since 1969 in the movement and alleged abuse by Sai Baba.<ref name=bbcd/> The show also featured allegations from Sai Baba critic Basava Premanand. Premanand stated in the documentary that, in his opinion, Sai Baba faked his materialisations.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n===Responses===\nSathya Sai Baba and his followers reject any allegations of misconduct.<ref name=funeral/> Devotee [[Bill Aitken (traveller)|Bill Aitken]] was quoted by ''[[The Week]]'' as saying that Sathya Sai Baba's reputation had not been harmed by the negative stories published about him. He said that the more detractors railed against Sathya Sai Baba, the more new devotees went to see him.<ref>Aitken, Bill (27 November 2005),{{cite web|url=http://www.the-week.com/25nov27/currentevents_article10.htm |title=Miracle of Welfare |accessdate=9 September 2006 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909111636/http://www.the-week.com/25nov27/currentevents_article10.htm |archivedate=9 September 2006  }}</ref>\n\nIn the article ''Divine Downfall'', published in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', Anil Kumar, the ex-principal of the Sathya Sai Educational Institute, said that he believed that the controversy was part of Sathya Sai Baba's divine plan and that all great religious teachers had to face criticism during their lives. Anil Kumar also said that allegations had been levelled at Sathya Sai Baba since childhood, but with every criticism he had become more and more triumphant.<ref name=\"divine\">Brown, Mick (28 October 2000). \"Divine Downfall\". Daily Telegraph.</ref>\n\nIn the book ''Redemptive Encounters: Three Modern Styles in the Hindu Tradition'', Lawrence A. Babb wrote of Sathya Sai Baba, \"Whoever he is, he is certainly more than the mere parlour magician many of his critics claim that he is.\"<ref name=\"BabbLawrence\"/>\n\nSathya Sai Baba publicly responded to the allegations on 25 December 2000:\n{{quote|Some people out of their mean-mindedness are trying to tarnish the image of Sai Baba. I am not after name and fame. So, I do not lose anything by their false allegations. My glory will go on increasing day by day. It will never diminish even a bit if they were to publicise their false allegations in the whole world in bold letters. Some devotees seem to be perturbed over these false statements. They are not true devotees at all. Having known the mighty power of Sai, why should they be afraid of the 'cawing of crows'? One should not get carried away by all that is written on walls, said in political meetings or the vulgar tales carried by the print media.<ref>Sathya Sai Speaks Vol.33, pg.389</ref>}}\n\n''[[The Times of India]]'' on 26 December 2000 quoted Sathya Sai Baba as saying: {{quote|[[Jesus Christ]] underwent many hardships, and was put to the cross because of jealousy. Many around him could not bear the good work he did and the large number of followers he gathered. One of his disciples, [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]], betrayed him. In those days there was one Judas, but today there are thousands. Just as that Judas was tempted to betray Jesus, the Judases of today, too, are bought out to lie. Jealousy was the motive behind the allegations levelled at him.<ref>Rao, Manu (26 December 2000), Sai Baba lashes out at detractors http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bangalore/sai-baba-lashes-out-at-detractors/articleshow/534425761.cms</ref>}}\n\nIn an official letter made public in December 2001, [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]] (then [[Prime Minister of India]] and a devotee of Sai Baba),<ref name=Palmer97-98 /> [[P. N. Bhagwati|P.N. Bhagwati]] (Former Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of India), [[Ranganath Misra]] (Chair Person, National Human Rights Commissioner of India and Former Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of India), [[Najma Heptulla]] (President of the Inter-Parliamentary Union; UNDP Distinguished Human Development Ambassador) and [[Shivraj V. Patil|Shivraj Patil]] (Member of Parliament, India; Formerly of the Lok Sabha & Union Minister) all signed the following statement:\n\n{{quote|We are deeply pained and anguished by the wild, reckless and concocted allegations made by certain vested interests and people against Bhagwan Sri Sathya Sai Baba. We would normally expect that responsible media would ascertain the true facts before printing such a calumny \u2013 especially when the person is revered globally as an embodiment of love and selfless service to humanity.<ref name=\"letterpmindia\">Letter from A.B. Vajpayee (the then Prime Minister of India), http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fline/fl2810/stories/20110520281002600.htm</ref><ref>Official Letter, http://www.saibaba.ws/images/letter_pm_india.gif</ref> }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Samuel H. Sandweiss|title=Sai Baba the Holy Man and the Psychiatrist|isbn=978-0-960-09581-0|year=1975|page=[https://archive.org/details/saibabaholymanps0000sand/page/240 240]|url=https://archive.org/details/saibabaholymanps0000sand/page/240}}\n* {{cite book|author=John S. Hislop|title=My Baba and I|isbn=978-0-960-09588-9|year=1985|url=https://archive.org/details/mybabai00hisl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Phyllis Krystal|title=Sai Baba: The Ultimate Experience|isbn=978-0-877-28794-0|year=1994|page=260}}\n* {{cite book|author=Don Mario Mazzoleni|title=A Catholic Priest Meets Sai Baba|isbn=978-0-962-98351-1|year=1994|page=[https://archive.org/details/catholicpriestme00mazz/page/285 285]|url=https://archive.org/details/catholicpriestme00mazz/page/285}}\n* {{cite book|author=Erlendur Haraldsson|title=Modern Miracles: An Investigative Report on These Psychic Phenomena Associated With Sathya Sai Baba|isbn=978-0-803-89384-9|year=1997|page=[https://archive.org/details/modernmiracles00erle/page/315 315]|url=https://archive.org/details/modernmiracles00erle/page/315}}\n* {{cite book|author=Vladimir Antonov|title=Sathya Sai Baba \u2013 The Christ of Our Days|isbn=978-1-438-25276-6|year=2008|page=38}}\n* {{cite book|author=Tommy S. W. Wong|title=How Sai Baba Attracts Without Direct Contact|isbn=978-1-448-60416-6|year=2009|page=108}}\n* {{cite book|author=Tulasi Srinivas|title=Winged Faith: Rethinking Globalization and Religious Pluralism Through the Sathya Sai Movement|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-14933-4|year=2010|page=430}}\n* {{cite book|author=David Smith|title=\"Hinduism\" Religions in the Modern World: Traditions and Transformations|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-85880-9|year=2016}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wikinews|Sai Baba upsets Telangana activists}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.sathyasai.org/ International Sai Organization]\n* {{Curlie|Society/Religion_and_Spirituality/Hinduism/Gurus_and_Saints/Sathya_Sai_Baba/}} \n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Sathya Sai Baba}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n80-7665}}\n\n{{Sathya Sai Baba}}\n{{Hindu reform movements}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT KEEP REMOVING THIS PAGE FROM THE \"HINDU SAINTS\" CATEGORY WITHOUT FIRST EXPLAINING YOUR REASONS ON THE TALK-PAGE.-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baba, Sathya Sai}}\n[[Category:Sathya Sai Baba| ]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian spiritual teachers]]\n[[Category:People from Anantapur district]]\n[[Category:People from Rayalaseema]]\n[[Category:People considered avatars by their followers]]\n[[Category:Puttaparthi]]\n[[Category:Psychokineticists]]\n[[Category:Religious pluralism]]\n[[Category:Self-declared messiahs]]\n[[Category:State funerals in India]]\n[[Category:Tantra]]\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Tantric practices]]\n[[Category:Telugu people]]\n[[Category:Burials in India]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: 2 million \u2192 2\u00a0million (6)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sathya_Sai_Baba"}
{"title_page": "Irshad (actor)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Irshad Ali\n| image       =\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_name  =  Irshad Ali\n| birth_place = [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]], India\n| nationality  = Indian\n| parents     = Abdu, Nafisa<ref name=\"mathrubhumi1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies/malayalam/400653/ |accessdate=24 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024035513/http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies/malayalam/400653/ |archivedate=24 October 2013 }}</ref>\n| spouse      =  Ramseena\n| children     =  Arshaq\n}}\n\n'''Irshad''' (also known Irshad ali)  is an Indian actor in [[Malayalam]] films. He hails from [[Kechery]], [[Thrissur]] .<ref>[http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?contentId=14801315&programId=1073752204&channelId=-1073750705&BV_ID=@@@&tabId=3] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203010126/http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?contentId=14801315&programId=1073752204&channelId=-1073750705&BV_ID=@@@&tabId=3 |date=3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nIrshad has acted in numerous award-winning [[Art film|art-house films]] including those directed by acclaimed filmmakers such as [[V. K. Pavithran|Pavithran]], [[T. V. Chandran]], [[P. T. Kunju Muhammed]], and [[K. R. Mohanan]]. He has also appeared in supporting roles in a few mainstream films. He debuted as an actor in [[Sibi Malayil]]'s campus story ''Pranayavarnangal'' (''Colours of Love'', 1998). ''Garshom'' (1999), his first offbeat film, gave him a place in [[parallel cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies/interview/863/ |accessdate=19 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219091055/http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies/interview/863/ |archivedate=19 December 2013 }}</ref> Several significant roles in parallel cinema made him a well-known face in art house movies. His notable films include T. V. Chandran's ''[[Dany (film)|Dany]]'' (2002), ''[[Paadam Onnu: Oru Vilapam]]'' (''Lesson One: A Wail'', 2003), ''[[Vilapangalkkappuram]]'' (2008) and ''[[Bhoomi Malayalam]]'' (''The Mother Earth'', 2009), P. T. Kunju Muhammed's ''[[Paradesi (2007 film)|Paradesi]]'' (''Foreigner'', 2007), [[Madhu Kaithapram]]'s ''[[Madhya Venal]]'' (2009), [[Priyanandanan]]'s ''[[Pulijanmam]]'' (''Tiger Life'', 2006) and ''[[Bhakthajanangalude Sradhakku]]'' (2011), and Dr. Biju's ''[[Veettilekkulla Vazhi]]'' (''The Way Home'', 2010).<ref>Rasmi Binoy. (5 May 2011). [http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article1993529.ece \"Career moves\"]. ''The Hindu''. Retrieved 9 May 2011.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is born to Puthenpura Nalakathu Abdu and Nafeesa, as fourth son among six children, at [[Kechery]], [[Thrissur]]. He has four brothers and a sister.<ref>[http://www.mangalam.com/mangalam-varika/254669?page=0,0 \u0d06\u0d23\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d2a\u0d46\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d23\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d1a\u0d41\u0d02\u0d2c\u0d3f\u0d1a\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d3e\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d \u0d32\u0d4b\u0d15\u0d02 \u0d07\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d1e\u0d4d\u0d1e\u0d41\u0d35\u0d40\u0d34\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d4b? | mangalam.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He is married to Ramseena, a bank employee. They have a son, Arshaq.<ref name=\"mathrubhumi1\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Role !!Director\n\n\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Operation Java]]''\n|\n|Tharun Moorthy\n|-\n|2020\n|''Silencer''\n|\n|[[Priyanandanan|Priyanandan]]\n|-\n|2019||''[[My Santa (2019 filim)]]''|| ||[[Sugeeth]]\n|-\n|2019||''Vikruthi''|| ||\n|-\n-\n|2019|| ''[[Thanneer Mathan Dinangal]]''||Principal || Gireesh A D\n|-\n|2019|| ''[[Sayanna Varthakal]]''||{{TBA}} || Arun Chandu\n|-\n|2018|| ''[[Joseph]]''|| Siddique || [[M. Padmakumar]]<ref>\n|-\n|2017|| ''[[Jomonte Suvisheshangal]]''||CA Joshy || [[Sathyan Anthikad]]\n|-\n|2017||  [[Rarandoi V