{"title_page": "Nana Tafregya Pallbearers", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Dancing Pallbearers]] {{R from merge}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability|1=Companies|date=April 2020}}\n\n#REDIRECT [[Dancing Pallbearers]] {{R from merge}}\n", "name_user": "Kwamevaughan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2190Redirected page toDancing Pallbearers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Nana_Tafregya_Pallbearers&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Agua Fria High School", "text_new": "{{coord|33|26|20.52|N|112|20|39.34|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name=[[Agua Fria Union High School]]\n|type=[[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|location= 530 E. Riley Drive<br>[[Avondale, Arizona|Avondale, AZ]]\n|established=1928 (Litchfield Park)<br>1956 (as Agua Fria)\n|grades=9-12\n|enrollment=1,761 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0400450&ID=040045000001 Agua Fria High School]</ref>\n|ratio=19.52<ref name=NCES></ref>\n|faculty=90.20 (FTE)<ref name=NCES></ref>\n|mascot=Owl\n|colors= {{Color box|Red|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|Grey|border=darkgray}} Red and grey\n|district=Agua Fria Union High School District\n|website={{URL|https://www.aguafria.org/afhs}}\n|motto=Honor First, Win or Lose}}\n'''Agua Fria High School''' is located in [[Avondale, Arizona]]. It is a part of the [[Agua Fria Union High School District]] and was its only school until 1999 when [[Millennium High School (Goodyear, Arizona)|Millennium High School]] was established.\n\nIt was established in 1928 as '''Litchfield Park High School'''. In 1956, the school relocated to Avondale and obtained its current name. In the 1982-83 school year, it was honored as a [[Blue Ribbon Schools Program|Blue Ribbon school]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ed.gov/programs/nclbbrs/list-1982.pdf |title= List 1982 |accessdate=2016-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630091138/http://www2.ed.gov/programs/nclbbrs/list-1982.pdf |archivedate=2014-06-30 }}</ref>\n\n==Fine arts==\nAgua Fria offers college preparatory coursework, along with career and technical education. Agua Fria also offers a respected music program; the Night Owl Jazz band regularly performs at jazz festivals throughout the Phoenix Area, and has qualified for the Arizona State Jazz Festival in both 2006, 2007 and 2009 when they were the first jazz ensemble to receive a rating of \"superior with distinctions\". Also in 2006, the Agua Fria Band of Owls was the first to receive a rating of \"superior with distinctions\" in the district.\n\n== Marching Band ==\nAgua Fria is home to the Band of Owls marching band under the direction of Jeremy Garcia.\n\n=== AFHS Fight Song ===\nThe Owl fight song goes as follows, \n\n\"Let's win this game;\n\nGo onward Owls, go!\n\nNever to yield\n\nA victory to the foe!\n\nOn to the goal;\n\nA gain on every play!\n\nFight Owls! Fight Owls!\n\nWin this game the same old way!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aguafria.org/site/default.aspx?DomainID=84|title=Owl Fight Song / Owl Fight song|website=AGUA FRIA HIGH SCHOOL|language=en|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nAgua Fria's athletic excellence is recognized state and nation wide. With the likes of Hall of Fame inductees [[Randall McDaniel]] to more recent stars like [[Everson Griffen]]. \n\nA football program that has boasted 5 state championships in Class 4A (1991, 1989, 1988, 1972, 1970). Along with countless NCAA Division 1 athletic scholarships.  \n\nThe track and field program is also worth recognizing. Under the direction of coach Ted Campbell, as well as Brian Bogen, the Owls morphed into perennial winners. Between 1997 and 2007, the boys' track team had a duel meet record of 112 wins and 13 losses, came home with countless invitational trophies, took first place in its region five years in a row (from 2004 to 2008), and won state titles back to back in 2006 and 2007.   \n\nThe men's basketball team has been prominent in tournaments and championships as well. Most recently, from 2007 to 2009, the varsity team made it to the 4A-I state finals, but fell short of winning the championship to [[Carrick Felix]]'s [[Millennium High School (Goodyear, Arizona)|Millennium High School]] (division rivals) and [[Sunnyslope High School]]. In 2016, they had again made it to the playoffs, but lost in the semi-final round to the team who ultimately won the state championship.\n\nAgua Fria's men's soccer team has also notched a 4A state championship (1999). Along with producing various playoff runs from 2006-2010. \n\nAgua Fria's cheerleading team has also been a frequent state and national contender in the past few years. During the 2015-2016 school year, head coach Torie Jones secured the team their first state bid in the school's history, and has secured a bid for them every year since. In her third year, she also took the varsity cheer team to finals at USA Nationals for the first time.\n\n==Solar panels==\nIn the late spring of 2011, covered parking with solar panel installations was scheduled to be added to Agua Fria and Millennium high schools; the district had already added solar panels to the roofs at [[Desert Edge High School]] and [[Verrado High School]] in 2010.<ref>http://www.azcentral.com/community/swvalley/articles/2011/01/16/20110116agua-fria-solar-panels.html</ref> It was estimated that some 40 percent of the entire district's energy needs would come from solar panels at its high schools upon completion.{{Cn|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n[[File:Aaron Altherr.png|thumb|180px|[[Aaron Altherr]]]]\n* [[Aaron Altherr]], baseball player\n* [[Cardell Camper]], baseball player\n* [[Chelsey Crisp]], actress\n* [[TempleOS|Terrance A. Davis]], computer programmer and [[programming language]] designer\n* [[Johnathan Doody]], murderer (with Alessandro Garcia) convicted in the [[Waddell Buddhist temple shooting|massacre of nine people]] at the Wat Promkunaram Buddhist Temple in [[Waddell, Arizona]]<ref name=\"phoenixnewtimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/news/dealing-with-a-confessed-serial-killer-6426015|title=Dealing with a Confessed Serial Killer|author=Tom Fitzpatrick|newspaper=Phoenix New Times|date=January 13, 1993|accessdate=December 18, 2015|quote=\"Alex Garcia, 17, a former student at Agua Fria High School... the school Garcia and Doody had attended.\"}}</ref>\n* [[Alessandro Garcia]], murderer (with Johnathan Doody) convicted in the massacre of nine people at the Wat Promkunaram Buddhist Temple in Waddell, Arizona<ref name=\"phoenixnewtimes\"></ref>\n* [[Shawn Gilbert]], baseball player\n* [[Everson Griffen]], [[American football|football]] player\n* [[Sam Johnson]], football player\n* [[Bill Lueck]], football player\n* [[Randall McDaniel]], NFL Hall of Fame\n* [[Sammy Solis]], baseball player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westvalleyview.com/content/agua-fria-grad-signs-nats|title=Agua Fria grad signs with Nats|work=[[West Valley View]]|first=Mike|last=Russo|date=August 19, 2010|accessdate=May 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082951/http://www.westvalleyview.com/content/agua-fria-grad-signs-nats|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Rusty Tillman]], football player\nEric L. Duncan, Wikipedia editor, master carpenter (retired), music producer and entrepreneur, 1984\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Coalition of Essential Schools]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Schools in Maricopa County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Arizona]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|33|26|20.52|N|112|20|39.34|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name=[[Agua Fria Union High School]]\n|type=[[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|location= 530 E. Riley Drive<br>[[Avondale, Arizona|Avondale, AZ]]\n|established=1928 (Litchfield Park)<br>1956 (as Agua Fria)\n|grades=9-12\n|enrollment=1,761 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0400450&ID=040045000001 Agua Fria High School]</ref>\n|ratio=19.52<ref name=NCES></ref>\n|faculty=90.20 (FTE)<ref name=NCES></ref>\n|mascot=Owl\n|colors= {{Color box|Red|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|Grey|border=darkgray}} Red and grey\n|district=Agua Fria Union High School District\n|website={{URL|https://www.aguafria.org/afhs}}\n|motto=Honor First, Win or Lose}}\n'''Agua Fria High School''' is located in [[Avondale, Arizona]]. It is a part of the [[Agua Fria Union High School District]] and was its only school until 1999 when [[Millennium High School (Goodyear, Arizona)|Millennium High School]] was built.\n\nIt was established in 1928 as '''Litchfield Park High School'''. In 1956, the school relocated to Avondale and obtained its current name. In the 1982-83 school year, it was honored as a [[Blue Ribbon Schools Program|Blue Ribbon school]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ed.gov/programs/nclbbrs/list-1982.pdf |title= List 1982 |accessdate=2016-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630091138/http://www2.ed.gov/programs/nclbbrs/list-1982.pdf |archivedate=2014-06-30 }}</ref>\n\n==Fine arts==\nAgua Fria offers college preparatory coursework, along with career and technical education. Agua Fria also offers a respected music program; the Night Owl Jazz band regularly performs at jazz festivals throughout the Phoenix Area, and has qualified for the Arizona State Jazz Festival in both 2006, 2007 and 2009 when they were the first jazz ensemble to receive a rating of \"superior with distinctions\". Also in 2006, the Agua Fria Band of Owls was the first to receive a rating of \"superior with distinctions\" in the district.\n\n== Marching Band ==\nAgua Fria is home to the Band of Owls marching band under the direction of Jeremy Garcia.\n\n=== AFHS Fight Song ===\nThe Owl fight song goes as follows, \n\n\"Let's win this game;\n\nGo onward Owls, go!\n\nNever to yield\n\nA victory to the foe!\n\nOn to the goal;\n\nA gain on every play!\n\nFight Owls! Fight Owls!\n\nWin this game the same old way!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aguafria.org/site/default.aspx?DomainID=84|title=Owl Fight Song / Owl Fight song|website=AGUA FRIA HIGH SCHOOL|language=en|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nAgua Fria's athletic excellence is recognized state and nation wide. With the likes of Hall of Fame inductees [[Randall McDaniel]] to more recent stars like [[Everson Griffen]]. \n\nA football program that has boasted 5 state championships in Class 4A (1991, 1989, 1988, 1972, 1970). Along with countless NCAA Division 1 athletic scholarships.  \n\nThe track and field program is also worth recognizing. Under the direction of coach Ted Campbell, as well as Brian Bogen, the Owls morphed into perennial winners. Between 1997 and 2007, the boys' track team had a duel meet record of 112 wins and 13 losses, came home with countless invitational trophies, took first place in its region five years in a row (from 2004 to 2008), and won state titles back to back in 2006 and 2007.   \n\nThe men's basketball team has been prominent in tournaments and championships as well. Most recently, from 2007 to 2009, the varsity team made it to the 4A-I state finals, but fell short of winning the championship to [[Carrick Felix]]'s [[Millennium High School (Goodyear, Arizona)|Millennium High School]] (division rivals) and [[Sunnyslope High School]]. In 2016, they had again made it to the playoffs, but lost in the semi-final round to the team who ultimately won the state championship.\n\nAgua Fria's men's soccer team has also notched a 4A state championship (1999). Along with producing various playoff runs from 2006-2010. \n\nAgua Fria's cheerleading team has also been a frequent state and national contender in the past few years. During the 2015-2016 school year, head coach Torie Jones secured the team their first state bid in the school's history, and has secured a bid for them every year since. In her third year, she also took the varsity cheer team to finals at USA Nationals for the first time.\n\n==Solar panels==\nIn the late spring of 2011, covered parking with solar panel installations was scheduled to be added to Agua Fria and Millennium high schools; the district had already added solar panels to the roofs at [[Desert Edge High School]] and [[Verrado High School]] in 2010.<ref>http://www.azcentral.com/community/swvalley/articles/2011/01/16/20110116agua-fria-solar-panels.html</ref> It was estimated that some 40 percent of the entire district's energy needs would come from solar panels at its high schools upon completion.{{Cn|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n[[File:Aaron Altherr.png|thumb|180px|[[Aaron Altherr]]]]\n* [[Aaron Altherr]], baseball player\n* [[Cardell Camper]], baseball player\n* [[Chelsey Crisp]], actress\n* [[TempleOS|Terrance A. Davis]], computer programmer and [[programming language]] designer\n* [[Johnathan Doody]], murderer (with Alessandro Garcia) convicted in the [[Waddell Buddhist temple shooting|massacre of nine people]] at the Wat Promkunaram Buddhist Temple in [[Waddell, Arizona]]<ref name=\"phoenixnewtimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/news/dealing-with-a-confessed-serial-killer-6426015|title=Dealing with a Confessed Serial Killer|author=Tom Fitzpatrick|newspaper=Phoenix New Times|date=January 13, 1993|accessdate=December 18, 2015|quote=\"Alex Garcia, 17, a former student at Agua Fria High School... the school Garcia and Doody had attended.\"}}</ref>\n* [[Alessandro Garcia]], murderer (with Johnathan Doody) convicted in the massacre of nine people at the Wat Promkunaram Buddhist Temple in Waddell, Arizona<ref name=\"phoenixnewtimes\"></ref>\n* [[Shawn Gilbert]], baseball player\n* [[Everson Griffen]], [[American football|football]] player\n* [[Sam Johnson]], football player\n* [[Bill Lueck]], football player\n* [[Randall McDaniel]], NFL Hall of Fame\n* [[Sammy Solis]], baseball player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westvalleyview.com/content/agua-fria-grad-signs-nats|title=Agua Fria grad signs with Nats|work=[[West Valley View]]|first=Mike|last=Russo|date=August 19, 2010|accessdate=May 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082951/http://www.westvalleyview.com/content/agua-fria-grad-signs-nats|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Rusty Tillman]], football player\nEric L. Duncan, Wikipedia editor, master carpenter (retired), music producer and entrepreneur, 1984\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Coalition of Essential Schools]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Schools in Maricopa County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Arizona]]\n[[Category:1956 establishments in Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "SWLinPHX", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed \"built\" to \"established\" to clarify campus was built years earlier but become its own entity in 1999", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agua_Fria_High_School"}
